<!-- Murray Loop -->
<div id="m1-murray" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Murray Loop — Distance to Ground Fault</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> You short the far end of two wires together, then measure resistance from your end. The ratio of your measured resistance to total loop resistance tells you exactly what fraction of the loop distance the fault is at. Works on any cable where you can reach both conductors.
<div class="mth">d = (2 × R_measured / R_loop) × L
  d         = distance to fault (same units as L)
  R_measured = resistance from test set to fault (Ω)
  R_loop    = total loop resistance tip+ring looped (Ω)
  L         = one-way cable length

Rearranged: d/L = R_measured / (R_loop/2)
Temp correction: R_actual = R_measured × [1 + 0.00393(T−20°C)]</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total loop resistance — tip+ring looped (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="mu-rl" placeholder="e.g. 200" oninput="calcMurray()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured resistance from test position (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="mu-rm" placeholder="e.g. 68" oninput="calcMurray()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>One-way cable length</label><input type="number" id="mu-l" placeholder="e.g. 12000" oninput="calcMurray()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Length unit</label><select id="mu-u" onchange="calcMurray()"><option value="ft">Feet</option><option value="kft">Kilofeet</option><option value="m">Meters</option><option value="km">km</option></select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable temp (°C) — for resistance correction</label><input type="number" id="mu-t" value="20" oninput="calcMurray()"></div>
<div id="mu-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="tip" style="margin-top:8px">Field tip: If you don't have total loop resistance, calculate it from AWG table × cable length × 2. Then verify by measuring directly before testing.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Murray Loop — AWG Loop Resistance Reference</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Use these to estimate total loop resistance when you know the cable gauge and length.</strong></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>AWG</th><th>Ω/1000 ft (one way)</th><th>Ω/1000 ft (loop)</th><th>Ω/mile (loop)</th></tr>
<tr><td>19</td><td>8.05</td><td>16.10</td><td>85.0</td></tr>
<tr><td>22</td><td>16.14</td><td>32.28</td><td>170.4</td></tr>
<tr><td>24</td><td>25.67</td><td>51.34</td><td>271.1</td></tr>
<tr><td>26</td><td>40.81</td><td>81.62</td><td>430.9</td></tr>
<tr><td>28</td><td>65.31</td><td>130.62</td><td>689.3</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Murray Loop — Worked Example</h3>
<div class="eli5">
  Cable: 24 AWG, 3 miles long. Fault on tip conductor. Loop resistance = 3 × 271.1 = 813.3 Ω.<br>
  Measured from CO: 280 Ω.<br>
  <div class="mth">d = (2 × 280 / 813.3) × 3 miles
d = (560 / 813.3) × 3 = 0.689 × 3 = 2.07 miles from CO</div>
  Cross-check: fault should be at 2.07 miles = 10,930 feet from the CO. Look for the nearest splice case, pedestal, or damage point.
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Capacitance Open Fault -->
<div id="m1-cap" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Capacitance Open Fault — Distance to Break</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> An open conductor acts like a capacitor. The capacitance you measure is proportional to the length of good cable before the break. If you know the cable's capacitance per unit length (from the AWG table), you can calculate exactly where the wire broke.
<div class="mth">d = C_measured / C_per_unit
  C_measured  = capacitance your meter reads (nF or pF)
  C_per_unit  = published capacitance for that gauge/type
  
Standard telecom pair capacitance:
  19 AWG PIC:  ~15.7 nF/mile  (8.3 pF/ft)
  22 AWG PIC:  ~15.7 nF/mile  (8.3 pF/ft)
  24 AWG PIC:  ~15.7 nF/mile  (8.3 pF/ft)
  26 AWG PIC:  ~15.7 nF/mile  (8.3 pF/ft)
  (Mutual capacitance is ~83 nF/km for PIC regardless of gauge)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured capacitance (nF)</label><input type="number" id="cap-c" placeholder="e.g. 32.5" oninput="calcCap()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable type / capacitance</label>
<select id="cap-type" onchange="capTypeChange()">
<option value="15.7">Standard PIC — 15.7 nF/mile</option>
<option value="16.0">Pulp (PASP) — 16.0 nF/mile</option>
<option value="custom">Custom value</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field" id="cap-custom-field" style="display:none"><label>Custom nF/mile</label><input type="number" id="cap-cu" placeholder="nF/mile" oninput="calcCap()"></div>
<div id="cap-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="wbox">Capacitance method only works on an open (broken) conductor with the far end floating. If the far end is grounded or there's a wet cable bridging the break, capacitance will read high and the result will be wrong.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Capacitance Fault — Quick Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Reading (nF)</th><th>Distance at 15.7 nF/mi</th><th>Feet</th></tr>
<tr><td>5</td><td>0.32 miles</td><td>1,675 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>10</td><td>0.64 miles</td><td>3,350 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>15</td><td>0.96 miles</td><td>5,060 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>20</td><td>1.27 miles</td><td>6,720 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>30</td><td>1.91 miles</td><td>10,100 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>47</td><td>3.0 miles</td><td>15,840 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>63</td><td>4.0 miles</td><td>21,120 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>78.5</td><td>5.0 miles</td><td>26,400 ft</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">If your meter reads in pF: divide by 1000 to get nF. At 83 nF/km: d(km) = nF ÷ 83. Then convert to feet: km × 3280.84.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Ohm's Law -->
<div id="m1-ohm" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Ohm's Law — V / I / R / P Solver</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Enter any two values. The other two calculate instantly.
<div class="mth">V = I × R        (Voltage = Current × Resistance)
I = V / R        (Current = Voltage / Resistance)
R = V / I        (Resistance = Voltage / Current)
P = V × I        (Power = Voltage × Current)
P = I² × R       (Power from current + resistance)
P = V² / R       (Power from voltage + resistance)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Voltage — V (volts)</label><input type="number" id="ohm-v" placeholder="leave blank to solve" oninput="calcOhm()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Current — I (amps)</label><input type="number" id="ohm-i" placeholder="leave blank to solve" oninput="calcOhm()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Resistance — R (ohms)</label><input type="number" id="ohm-r" placeholder="leave blank to solve" oninput="calcOhm()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Power — P (watts)</label><input type="number" id="ohm-p" placeholder="leave blank to solve" oninput="calcOhm()"></div>
<div id="ohm-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="tip">Telecom tip: −48V plant at 180A = 8,640W = 8.64 kW. DC watt = V × I, no power factor correction needed.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Ohm's Law — Telecom Quick Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Situation</th><th>Formula</th><th>Telecom example</th></tr>
<tr><td>Fault current</td><td>I = V/R</td><td>52V ÷ 100Ω = 0.52A</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cable drop</td><td>V = I × R</td><td>0.18A × 200Ω = 36V drop</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fault resistance</td><td>R = V/I</td><td>48V ÷ 0.24A = 200Ω</td></tr>
<tr><td>DC load watts</td><td>P = V × I</td><td>52V × 180A = 9.36 kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>Shunt check</td><td>I = mV ÷ (shunt mV/A)</td><td>48mV ÷ 50mV/100A = 96A</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Standard −48V Telco DC Voltages</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Condition</th><th>Voltage</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>Float (normal)</td><td>−52 to −54V</td><td>Rectifiers active</td></tr>
<tr><td>Battery only</td><td>−48 to −52V</td><td>Early discharge</td></tr>
<tr><td>Low alarm</td><td>≈ −42.75V</td><td>1.78V/cell</td></tr>
<tr><td>Low disconnect</td><td>≈ −40V</td><td>1.67V/cell — load shed</td></tr>
<tr><td>High alarm</td><td>≈ −56.7V</td><td>2.36V/cell</td></tr>
<tr><td>Equalize</td><td>−55.9 to −57.6V</td><td>2.33–2.40V/cell</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- DC Loop Resistance -->
<div id="m1-dcloop" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>DC Loop Resistance Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> DC loop resistance is the total resistance of the wire path from your test point to the far end and back. It's the foundation of copper qualification — you need this to verify the pair is suitable for DSL, T1, or voice service.
<div class="mth">R_loop = 2 × L × R_per_unit
  L         = one-way length
  R_per_unit = resistance per unit length (from AWG table)

Max loop resistance limits:
  POTS/analog:  1,700 Ω (~800mA ringer current)
  ADSL2+:        ~900 Ω practical limit
  VDSL2-17a:     ~100 Ω (short loops only)
  T1/DS1 24AWG:  ~750 Ω (limited by span loss)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable gauge</label>
<select id="dcl-awg" onchange="calcDCL()">
<option value="8.05">19 AWG — 8.05 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="16.14">22 AWG — 16.14 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="25.67" selected>24 AWG — 25.67 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="40.81">26 AWG — 40.81 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="custom">Custom Ω/kft</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field" id="dcl-custom-f" style="display:none"><label>Custom Ω/kft</label><input type="number" id="dcl-cu" oninput="calcDCL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>One-way length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="dcl-l" placeholder="e.g. 12000" oninput="calcDCL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Number of bridge taps</label><input type="number" id="dcl-bt" value="0" min="0" oninput="calcDCL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Bridge tap length each (feet)</label><input type="number" id="dcl-btl" value="0" oninput="calcDCL()"></div>
<div id="dcl-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>DC Loop R — AWG Quick Lookup</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>AWG</th><th>Ω/1000ft</th><th>Ω/mile</th><th>Max ADSL2+ reach</th></tr>
<tr><td>19</td><td>8.05</td><td>42.5</td><td>>5 miles</td></tr>
<tr><td>22</td><td>16.14</td><td>85.2</td><td>~5.3 miles</td></tr>
<tr><td>24</td><td>25.67</td><td>135.5</td><td>~3.3 miles</td></tr>
<tr><td>26</td><td>40.81</td><td>215.5</td><td>~2.1 miles</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">Bridge taps add to effective loop resistance. Each 500 ft bridge tap on 24 AWG adds ~26Ω to loop R — and they kill DSL sync rate even more than the resistance suggests due to reflections.</div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Qualification Limits</h3>
<table class="tbl">
