<!-- Insulation Resistance -->
<div id="m1-ir" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Insulation Resistance Normalizer</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Insulation resistance (IR) changes with cable length — longer cables have more insulation surface and therefore lower parallel IR. Always normalize to 1 mile (or 1 km) before comparing results or making a pass/fail judgment.
<div class="mth">IR_normalized = IR_measured × L_miles
  (multiply by length in miles to get MΩ·miles)

Pass thresholds (Telcordia TR-NWT-000057):
  New installation:       ≥ 1,000 MΩ·mile (wet)
  Acceptable service:     ≥   100 MΩ·mile
  Marginal — investigate: ≥    10 MΩ·mile
  Fail — replace cable:   <    10 MΩ·mile

Temperature correction (doubles every 10°C rise above 68°F):
  IR_corrected = IR_measured × 2^((T_meas − 68°F)/18)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured IR (MΩ)</label><input type="number" id="ir-m" placeholder="e.g. 45" oninput="calcIR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="ir-l" placeholder="e.g. 15840" oninput="calcIR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Test voltage</label>
<select id="ir-v">
<option value="500">500V (standard)</option>
<option value="1000">1,000V (long span)</option>
<option value="100">100V (sensitive circuits)</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable temperature (°F)</label><input type="number" id="ir-t" value="68" oninput="calcIR()"></div>
<div id="ir-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>IR Test — Field Interpretation Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>IR·miles (MΩ)</th><th>Condition</th><th>Action</th></tr>
<tr><td class="pass">>1,000</td><td class="pass">Excellent</td><td>No action</td></tr>
<tr><td class="pass">100–1,000</td><td class="pass">Good</td><td>Normal service</td></tr>
<tr><td class="warn">10–100</td><td class="warn">Marginal</td><td>Monitor, check splices</td></tr>
<tr><td class="fail"><10</td><td class="fail">Fail</td><td>Locate and replace</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Common IR failure patterns:</strong>
<br>• Rain-sensitive (IR drops during rain, recovers when dry) → wet splice, bad end cap, deteriorated insulation
<br>• Consistent low IR → direct cable damage, buried splice with water infiltration  
<br>• Asymmetric (T-G ≠ R-G) → one conductor damaged; check for staple hits, rodent damage
<br>• Very low on all pairs in cable → sheath failure, flooding</div>
<div class="wbox">Always test T-G, R-G, and T-R. A ground fault will show on T-G or R-G. A longitudinal/pair fault shows T-R. All three low = major sheath damage.</div>
</div>
</div>
