<!-- RFL McCarty -->
<div id="m2-rfl" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>RFL — McCarty Method (DTS / DTF)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> When a fault occurs on one conductor of a pair, you use the good conductor as the return path. By measuring resistance from both ends (called Distance-To-Short from each end), you can calculate exactly where the fault is, even accounting for temperature differences between the cable's temperature and the reference temperature.
<div class="mth">McCarty formula:
  d = L × (DTS_A / (DTS_A + DTF_B))

Where:
  d     = distance from End A to fault
  L     = total one-way loop length
  DTS_A = resistance measured End A to fault
  DTF_B = resistance measured End B to fault

For 2% twist correction (lay of pair unequal):
  multiply result by 1.02 for conservative estimate

Temperature correction for resistance measurements:
  R_corrected = R_measured / [1 + 0.00393 × (T°C − 20)]</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total cable length (one way)</label><input type="number" id="rfl-l" placeholder="e.g. 18000" oninput="calcRFL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Length unit</label>
<select id="rfl-u" onchange="calcRFL()">
<option value="1">Feet</option>
<option value="0.001">Kilofeet</option>
<option value="3.28084">Meters</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>DTS — resistance from End A (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="rfl-a" placeholder="e.g. 340" oninput="calcRFL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>DTF — resistance from End B (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="rfl-b" placeholder="e.g> 460" oninput="calcRFL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Apply 2% twist correction?</label>
<select id="rfl-tw" onchange="calcRFL()">
<option value="1">No correction</option>
<option value="1.02">Yes — add 2%</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable temperature (°C)</label><input type="number" id="rfl-t" value="20" oninput="calcRFL()"></div>
<div id="rfl-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>RFL Theory & Field Setup</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Test setup — what you need:</strong><br>
1. Locate the same pair at both ends (CO and far end cabinet/pedestal)<br>
2. At the far end: short the faulted conductor to a known-good conductor on the SAME pair. Note which two conductors you've shorted.<br>
3. At End A (CO): measure resistance T-to-R (or tip to shorted ring)<br>
4. Have someone at End B measure resistance T-to-R from their end<br>
5. Plug both resistance values into the McCarty formula<br>
<br><strong>Common RFL mistakes:</strong></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Wrong gauge:</strong> If the cable changes gauge (24→26 AWG), the resistance ratio changes midspan. You must account for each section separately.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Bridged tap:</strong> A bridge tap creates a parallel resistance path that throws off the ratio. Remove or account for taps before testing.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Temperature variation:</strong> Cable in conduit may be a different temperature than cable exposed outdoors. Use the temperature correction formula for accuracy.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Wet cable:</strong> Longitudinal water in the sheath can create a distributed fault that looks like a single point fault but isn't. If your result moves when you re-test, suspect distributed damage.</span></div>
<div class="tip">Best practice: confirm the RFL result with a TDR waveform test. RFL gives distance, TDR gives a picture. They should agree within 5%.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Murray Bridge -->
<div id="m2-murray2" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Murray Loop — Bridge Arm Method (R1/R2)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The classical Murray loop uses a Wheatstone bridge with adjustable arms R1 and R2. You balance the bridge (null the galvanometer), then read the ratio R1/(R1+R2). That ratio multiplied by total loop length is the distance to fault.
<div class="mth">At bridge balance (galvanometer = 0):
  d = [R1 / (R1 + R2)] × 2L

Where:
  d  = distance from test point to fault
  R1 = resistance of arm R1 at balance (Ω)
  R2 = resistance of arm R2 at balance (Ω)
  L  = one-way cable length

If R1 + R2 = fixed (e.g. 1000 Ω decade box):
  Fault % = R1 / (R1 + R2) × 100
  d = (fault %) × 2L / 100</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>R1 at balance (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="mb-r1" placeholder="e.g. 340" oninput="calcMB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R2 at balance (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="mb-r2" placeholder="e.g. 660" oninput="calcMB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>One-way cable length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="mb-l" placeholder="e.g. 12000" oninput="calcMB()"></div>
<div id="mb-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Bridge Arm Ratios — Quick Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>R1</th><th>R2</th><th>Ratio R1/(R1+R2)</th><th>Fault at (% of loop)</th></tr>
<tr><td>100</td><td>900</td><td>0.100</td><td>10%</td></tr>
<tr><td>250</td><td>750</td><td>0.250</td><td>25%</td></tr>
<tr><td>500</td><td>500</td><td>0.500</td><td>50% (midpoint)</td></tr>
<tr><td>680</td><td>320</td><td>0.680</td><td>68%</td></tr>
<tr><td>800</td><td>200</td><td>0.800</td><td>80%</td></tr>
<tr><td>900</td><td>100</td><td>0.900</td><td>90%</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">When using a 1,000 Ω decade box (R1+R2=1,000 fixed), the R1 reading in ohms directly equals the percentage × 10. R1=340 → fault is at 34% of the loop length from your end.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Varley Loop -->
<div id="m2-varley" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Varley Loop Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The Varley loop is a variation of Murray loop that uses a ratio arm and a variable resistor (S). It's more precise because it's a true null measurement, and it can locate faults even when the loop resistance is not precisely known. Commonly used in older test equipment.
<div class="mth">Varley formula:
  d = L × (2 × R_c − S) / (2 × R_c)

Where:
  d   = distance to fault from test end
  L   = one-way cable length
  R_c = resistance of one conductor (half loop)
  S   = the slide wire/variable setting at null

Alternative form:
  Fault resistance Rf = S × (R_loop / 2) − R_c

If the fault has resistance > 0:
  The measured distance will appear SHORTER than actual
  (fault resistance effectively adds to the far end conductor)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>One conductor resistance — R_c (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="vl-rc" placeholder="e.g. 150" oninput="calcVL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Variable S at balance (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="vl-s" placeholder="e.g. 95" oninput="calcVL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>One-way cable length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="vl-l" placeholder="e.g. 12000" oninput="calcVL()"></div>
<div id="vl-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Varley vs Murray — When to Use Which</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Situation</th><th>Best method</th><th>Why</th></tr>
<tr><td>Low resistance fault (&lt;1Ω)</td><td>Murray</td><td>Simple, works well for solid shorts</td></tr>
<tr><td>High resistance fault (>100Ω)</td><td>Varley</td><td>Better null precision at high R</td></tr>
<tr><td>Unknown loop R</td><td>Varley</td><td>Loop R not required for formula</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wet fault (variable R)</td><td>Either with TDR</td><td>Resistance instability — confirm with TDR</td></tr>
<tr><td>Field test set only</td><td>Murray (electronic)</td><td>Built into all modern copper test sets</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="wbox">Varley loop requires precise knowledge of one conductor's resistance. If there's a splice loss discrepancy or gauge change, recalculate R_c for each section. A 5% error in R_c results in a 5% location error.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Wheatstone Balance -->
<div id="m2-wbal" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Wheatstone Bridge — Solve for Unknown Rx</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Four resistors in a diamond pattern. When the bridge is balanced (no current through the galvanometer), the ratio of the known arms equals the ratio of the unknown arms. This lets you measure resistance with extreme precision by finding the balance point.
<div class="mth">Bridge balance condition:
  R1/R2 = R3/Rx
  
Solving for unknown Rx:
  Rx = (R2 × R3) / R1

Where:
  R1, R2, R3 = known resistors (arms of the bridge)
  Rx         = unknown resistance being measured

Wheatstone bridge diagram:
  Battery(+) ──┬─── R1 ───┬─── (-)
               │           │
              R2           R3
               │           │
               └─── Rx ───┘
               (galvanometer between center nodes)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>R1 (known — top left, Ω)</label><input type="number" id="wb-r1" placeholder="e.g. 100" oninput="calcWB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R2 (known — bottom left, Ω)</label><input type="number" id="wb-r2" placeholder="e.g. 100" oninput="calcWB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R3 (known — top right, Ω)</label><input type="number" id="wb-r3" placeholder="e.g. 247.5" oninput="calcWB()"></div>
<div id="wb-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="tip">When R1 = R2 (ratio arms are equal), the bridge simplifies to Rx = R3. This is the most common configuration — equal ratio arms give you maximum sensitivity at the balance point.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Wheatstone Bridge — Theory</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Why it's so accurate:</strong> At balance, no current flows through the galvanometer. This means you're not measuring the galvanometer's resistance (which would cause loading errors). You're detecting a true null — extremely sensitive to tiny changes.
<br><br>
<strong>Copper plant applications:</strong><br>
• Murray loop test set IS a Wheatstone bridge with one arm being the cable<br>
• Varley loop = modified Wheatstone with sliding wire<br>
• Low-resistance measurements (shunt checks, ground continuity)<br>
• Insulation resistance bridges (megohm range bridges)<br>
<br>
<strong>Bridge sensitivity:</strong> Best sensitivity occurs when all four arms are equal. As the ratio becomes extreme (R1 >> R2 or vice versa), sensitivity drops — you may miss the null point.</div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Quick Balance Check</h3>
<div class="field"><label>Test: ratio check — does R1/R2 = R3/Rx?</label></div>
<div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:8px">
<div class="field"><label>R1</label><input type="number" id="wbc-r1" placeholder="R1" oninput="calcWBC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R2</label><input type="number" id="wbc-r2" placeholder="R2" oninput="calcWBC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R3</label><input type="number" id="wbc-r3" placeholder="R3" oninput="calcWBC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Rx (measured)</label><input type="number" id="wbc-rx" placeholder="Rx" oninput="calcWBC()"></div>
</div>
<div id="wbc-result"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Unbalanced Bridge -->
<div id="m2-wunbal" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Unbalanced Wheatstone Bridge — Vout</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> When the bridge is NOT balanced, a voltage appears across the galvanometer terminals. The magnitude tells you how far off from balance you are. Used in transducer circuits (pressure sensors, temperature sensors) that use a bridge to measure changes.
<div class="mth">V_out = V_in × [(R3/(R1+R3)) − (Rx/(R2+Rx))]

Where:
  V_in = supply voltage across the bridge
  R1, R2, R3, Rx = four bridge arms

Linearized sensitivity for small changes (ΔRx &lt;&lt; Rx):
  ΔV_out ≈ (V_in / 4) × (ΔRx / Rx)

At balance: V_out = 0
Positive V_out: Rx is LARGER than balance value
Negative V_out: Rx is SMALLER than balance value</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Supply voltage V_in (V)</label><input type="number" id="ub-vi" placeholder="e.g. 9" oninput="calcUB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R1 (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="ub-r1" placeholder="e.g. 1000" oninput="calcUB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R2 (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="ub-r2" placeholder="e.g. 1000" oninput="calcUB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>R3 (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="ub-r3" placeholder="e.g. 1000" oninput="calcUB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Rx — actual/measured (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="ub-rx" placeholder="e.g. 1050" oninput="calcUB()"></div>
<div id="ub-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Bridge Applications in CO Power</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>The Wheatstone bridge shows up more than you'd think in the CO:</strong>
<br><br>
<strong>Shunt measurement:</strong> Your plant shunt IS a precision resistor (bridge arm). The mV reading across it is proportional to current — same principle as an unbalanced bridge.
<br><br>
<strong>Battery monitor:</strong> Some battery monitoring systems use bridge circuits to detect cell voltage imbalance across a string.
<br><br>
<strong>Ground fault relays:</strong> Many ground detection circuits use a bridge with the earth resistance as one arm — when it's too low (fault), the bridge goes out of balance and trips an alarm.
<br><br>
<strong>RTD temperature sensors:</strong> The RTD (Resistance Temperature Detector) in your HVAC and battery room thermostats is typically measured via a Wheatstone bridge — resistance changes with temperature, and the bridge converts that to a voltage that drives the controller.</div>
<div class="tip">Understanding bridge circuits makes you better at troubleshooting — whenever you see a relay that responds to resistance changes (ground detection, over-temperature, overcurrent), think Wheatstone bridge.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div><!-- end Module 2 -->

