<!-- Noise & Induction -->
<div id="m3-noise" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Longitudinal Balance Analysis</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Longitudinal balance measures how well a pair rejects common-mode noise (like 60 Hz power line hum). A perfectly balanced pair cancels hum completely — equal voltages on tip and ring cancel each other. Any imbalance lets noise through as metallic (T-R) noise that corrupts data.
<div class="mth">Longitudinal Balance Loss (LBL):
  LBL = 20 × log10(V_longitudinal / V_metallic)  dB
  
  &gt; 60 dB: Excellent balance
  50–60 dB: Good (acceptable for DSL)
  40–50 dB: Fair (may cause noise issues)
  &lt; 40 dB: Poor — investigate pair and splices

Metallic noise from imbalance:
  V_metallic ≈ V_longitudinal / 10^(LBL/20)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Longitudinal voltage T+R to ground (mVrms)</label><input type="number" id="lb-vl" placeholder="e.g. 500" oninput="calcLB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Metallic voltage T-R (mVrms)</label><input type="number" id="lb-vm" placeholder="e.g. 1.5" oninput="calcLB()"></div>
<div id="lb-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Power Influence Estimator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Estimate expected longitudinal induced voltage from a power line running parallel to your cable.</strong>
<div class="mth">V_induced ≈ (2π × f × M × I_power × L) 
  M = mutual inductance (H/mile, ~0.001 for typical separation)
  I_power = power line current (A)
  L = parallel exposure length (miles)
  f = frequency (60 Hz)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Power line current (A)</label><input type="number" id="pi-i" placeholder="e.g. 100" oninput="calcPI()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Parallel exposure length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="pi-l" placeholder="e.g. 2640" oninput="calcPI()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Separation distance (feet)</label>
<select id="pi-sep" onchange="calcPI()">
<option value="0.003">5 ft — same pole (worst case)</option>
<option value="0.001">10 ft — adjacent poles</option>
<option value="0.0005">25 ft — parallel street</option>
<option value="0.0002">50+ ft — open field</option>
</select></div>
<div id="pi-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Noise Source Diagnosis Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause</th><th>Test</th></tr>
<tr><td>60 Hz hum, metallic</td><td>Poor pair balance, bad splice</td><td>LBL test, locate splice</td></tr>
<tr><td>60 Hz hum, longitudinal</td><td>Power line induction, no ground</td><td>Measure V T+R to GND</td></tr>
<tr><td>120/180 Hz buzz</td><td>Rectifier harmonics from power</td><td>Frequency analysis</td></tr>
<tr><td>Impulse noise (clicks)</td><td>Lightning, switching transients</td><td>Impulse noise test (Sidekick)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wideband noise floor raised</td><td>AM radio ingress, bad sheath</td><td>Check IR, look for AM broadcast nearby</td></tr>
<tr><td>Narrowband tones</td><td>NEXT/FEXT crosstalk from T1 or ADSL</td><td>NEXT test, check binder mates</td></tr>
<tr><td>Noise only in rain</td><td>Wet splice or corroded terminal</td><td>IR test after rain, tone test splices</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>NEXT / FEXT Crosstalk Estimator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>NEXT (Near-End Crosstalk)</strong> — interference picked up at the transmit end from adjacent pairs.<br>
<strong>FEXT (Far-End Crosstalk)</strong> — interference at the receive end.<br>
<div class="mth">NEXT loss (approx):   NL ≈ −15 − 15×log10(f_MHz)  dB
FEXT loss (approx):   FL ≈ −25 − 20×log10(f_MHz) − 10×log10(L_kft)  dB

Higher loss = LESS crosstalk interference
ADSL2+ NEXT requirement: &gt; 40 dB at 2.2 MHz
T1 (AMI) NEXT requirement: &gt; 40 dB at 772 kHz</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Test frequency (MHz)</label><input type="number" id="nx-f" placeholder="e.g. 2.2" step="0.1" oninput="calcNX()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Loop length (kft)</label><input type="number" id="nx-l" placeholder="e.g. 12" oninput="calcNX()"></div>
<div id="nx-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- SNR / Insertion Loss -->
<div id="m3-snr" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Insertion Loss Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Insertion loss is how much a cable attenuates a signal at a specific frequency. DSL equipment reports this as a key metric during line testing. Higher insertion loss = weaker signal = slower speeds or no sync.
<div class="mth">Insertion loss (dB) for loaded cable:
  IL = α × L
  α (attenuation constant, dB/kft) varies with frequency:

For 24 AWG PIC at temperature T (°F):
  300 kHz (ADSL):  α ≈ 2.0 dB/kft
  1 MHz (VDSL2):   α ≈ 3.7 dB/kft
  2.2 MHz (ADSL2+):α ≈ 5.0 dB/kft
  8.5 MHz (VDSL2-8a): α ≈ 9.5 dB/kft
  17.6 MHz (VDSL2-17a): α ≈ 14 dB/kft

Temp correction: add 0.2% per °F above 68°F</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable gauge</label>
<select id="il-awg" onchange="calcIL()">
<option value="19">19 AWG</option>
<option value="22">22 AWG</option>
<option value="24" selected>24 AWG</option>
<option value="26">26 AWG</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Loop length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="il-l" placeholder="e.g. 10000" oninput="calcIL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Test frequency</label>
<select id="il-freq" onchange="calcIL()">
<option value="adsl">300 kHz — ADSL reference</option>
<option value="adsl2p">1.1 MHz — ADSL2+ midband</option>
<option value="vdsl8">8.5 MHz — VDSL2 profile 8a</option>
<option value="vdsl17" selected>17.6 MHz — VDSL2 profile 17a</option>
<option value="t1">772 kHz — T1 / DS1</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable temperature (°F)</label><input type="number" id="il-t" value="68" oninput="calcIL()"></div>
<div id="il-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>SNR Margin Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> SNR margin is the buffer between your received signal level and the minimum needed for error-free operation. A DSL modem typically needs 6 dB minimum SNR margin. Higher is better, but DSL standards allow interleaving depth to trade latency for error correction.
<div class="mth">SNR_margin = SNR_measured − SNR_minimum
  
  &gt; 20 dB: Excellent — stable, high speed
  12–20 dB: Good — reliable service
   6–12 dB: Acceptable — may have occasional errors
   3–6 dB:  Marginal — frequent retrain likely
   &lt; 3 dB:  Fail — won't hold sync

Noise floor reference (24 AWG, 1 MHz):
  Thermal noise:  ~−140 dBm/Hz
  Typical ADSL noise floor: −90 to −100 dBm/Hz</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured downstream SNR (dB) — from modem stats</label><input type="number" id="snr-m" placeholder="e.g. 18" oninput="calcSNR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured downstream attenuation (dB)</label><input type="number" id="snr-a" placeholder="e.g. 32" oninput="calcSNR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Modem target SNR margin (dB)</label><input type="number" id="snr-t" value="6" oninput="calcSNR()"></div>
<div id="snr-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Sync Rate Estimator -->
<div id="m3-sync" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>DSL Sync Rate Estimator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> This estimates what sync rate you should expect given your measured loop parameters. It's a rough estimate — actual sync depends on noise environment, modem capabilities, DSLAM configuration, and DSLAM-side profiles. Use this to set expectations and identify when a line is performing significantly below potential.
<div class="mth">Capacity estimate (Shannon-based approximation):
  C ≈ B × log2(1 + SNR_linear)
  SNR_linear = 10^(SNR_dB / 10)
  B = usable bandwidth for profile

ADSL2+ downstream bandwidth ≈ 2.2 MHz
VDSL2-17a downstream bandwidth ≈ 17.6 MHz
(accounting for upstream and guard bands)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured SNR margin (dB)</label><input type="number" id="sy-snr" placeholder="e.g. 14" oninput="calcSync()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Loop attenuation (dB) — from modem</label><input type="number" id="sy-att" placeholder="e.g. 28" oninput="calcSync()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>DSL profile</label>
<select id="sy-prof" onchange="calcSync()">
<option value="adsl2p">ADSL2+</option>
<option value="vdsl8">VDSL2 Profile 8a</option>
<option value="vdsl17" selected>VDSL2 Profile 17a</option>
<option value="vdsl30">VDSL2 Profile 30a</option>
</select></div>
<div id="sy-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="wbox" style="margin-top:8px">This is an approximation only. Actual sync rate depends on DSLAM configuration, interleave settings, power spectral density masks, and the noise environment. Use for estimating expected range — not for exact predictions.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>DSL Troubleshooting Decision Tree</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>No sync at all:</strong> Check loop resistance (&lt;900Ω ADSL2+, &lt;200Ω VDSL2-17a). Check for foreign voltage. Verify wiring at CPE jack. Verify DSLAM port is active.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Sync but slow:</strong> Check attenuation vs length. If attenuation is high for the length → bad splice or wet cable. Check SNR margin — if low → noise problem, not just length.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Intermittent drops:</strong> Check impulse noise (Sidekick VIP). Check IR — often goes marginal in rain. Check CPE microfilter placement. Verify no extension wiring with old bridge taps.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Slow upstream only:</strong> Check for AM radio ingress (strong AM transmitters below 1.7 MHz). Check UPBO (upstream power back-off) settings on DSLAM. Check NEXT from T1s in same binder.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>All pairs in cable affected:</strong> Sheath failure or flooding — check cable IR. Or macro-level noise source (power line cross, broadcast station, carrier frequency interference).</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">6</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Customer CPE self-install:</strong> Verify microfilter on every non-DSL phone jack. Check if customer wiring has open bridge taps. Try direct connection at NID before troubleshooting further.</span></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
