<!-- OSP Chronic Diagnostic -->
<div id="m4-diag" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>OSP Chronic Grounding Diagnostic — 9-Step</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Chronic grounding problems are the most misdiagnosed issues in the plant. Before you spend weeks chasing symptoms, run through this systematic diagnostic to identify the root cause.
</div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Measure the battery bus voltage at the CO main BDFB.</strong> Should be −52 to −54V floating. If low (&lt;−48V), you have a battery or rectifier problem — not a grounding problem. Stop here.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Check CO ground bus resistance to building steel.</strong> Should be &lt;1Ω. Higher means the CO ground system is compromised. Measure with a 4-wire (Kelvin) measurement to eliminate lead resistance.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Measure foreign AC voltage on the cable pair (T-G and R-G).</strong> More than 0.5 Vrms suggests inadequate neutralization transformer or missing protector ground. More than 5 Vrms is an active induction problem.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Check all ground rod connections.</strong> Use a clamp-on ground resistance meter (Fluke 1630) to measure each rod non-invasively. Target: &lt;25Ω for OSP, &lt;5Ω for CO. Measure in dry conditions — wet soil gives falsely low readings.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Inspect cable shield bonding at every accessible splice point.</strong> Shield connections that are corroded, missing, or broken cause shield discontinuities that allow ground potential differences to appear on conductors.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">6</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Check neutralizing transformer (NTx) installation and sizing.</strong> NTx should be installed where cable enters an area of GPR risk. Verify the NTx is correctly sized for the expected fault current × parallel length product.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">7</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Measure shield continuity end-to-end.</strong> Measure resistance of cable shield from CO to terminal. Compare to calculated value from shield resistance table. A high reading indicates a shield break.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">8</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Check gas tube protectors at serving terminal.</strong> Failed protectors can hold a metallic fault to ground. Remove and test each protector — they should read open when not activated.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">9</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Document and compare to historical records.</strong> Grounding problems often develop gradually. Comparing current measurements to previous readings identifies trends before they become service outages.</span></div>
<div class="wbox" style="margin-top:8px">Ground resistance measurements taken during or immediately after rain are unreliable. Soil moisture dramatically reduces apparent ground resistance. Always note weather conditions with readings.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Ground Rod — Dwight Formula</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The Dwight formula calculates the theoretical resistance of a single ground rod driven into soil of a known resistivity. Real-world values vary with soil moisture and mineral content.
<div class="mth">R = (ρ / 2πL) × [ln(4L/d) − 1]

  R = ground rod resistance (Ω)
  ρ = soil resistivity (Ω·cm)
  L = rod length (cm)
  d = rod diameter (cm)
  ln = natural logarithm

Typical soil resistivities (Ω·cm):
  Wet clay:      100–1,000
  Loam/garden:   1,000–10,000
  Sand (wet):    10,000–30,000
  Sand (dry):    30,000–100,000
  Gravel:        100,000–1,000,000</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Rod length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="gr-l" value="8" oninput="calcGR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Rod diameter (inches)</label><input type="number" id="gr-d" value="0.625" step="0.125" oninput="calcGR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Soil resistivity (Ω·cm)</label>
<select id="gr-rho" onchange="calcGR()">
<option value="500">Wet clay — 500 Ω·cm</option>
<option value="3000" selected>Loam/soil — 3,000 Ω·cm</option>
<option value="15000">Wet sand — 15,000 Ω·cm</option>
<option value="50000">Dry sand — 50,000 Ω·cm</option>
<option value="custom">Custom value</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field" id="gr-custom-f" style="display:none"><label>Custom ρ (Ω·cm)</label><input type="number" id="gr-cu" oninput="calcGR()"></div>
<div id="gr-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="tip">To achieve &lt;25Ω in typical soil (3,000 Ω·cm), you generally need 2–3 rods in parallel separated by at least their length. Rods too close together have diminishing returns due to overlapping resistance zones.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Ground Potential Rise -->
<div id="m4-gpr" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Ground Potential Rise (GPR) — IEEE 80</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> During a power line fault, massive current flows through the earth to the nearest substation ground. This raises the voltage of the local earth relative to the "true" remote earth. Telecom cables entering the substation area carry this elevated voltage back to the CO — where it can damage equipment and injure people.
<div class="mth">GPR = I_fault × R_ground

  I_fault  = fault current (A) — from power company
  R_ground = substation ground resistance (Ω)

Touch voltage (person standing, touching structure):
  V_touch = GPR × (R_body / (R_body + R_ground_path))
  R_body ≈ 1,000 Ω (IEEE 80)
  Safe touch voltage limit ≈ 50V (OSHA)

Step voltage (person walking):
  V_step = ρ × I_fault × (1/(2π)) × (1/x1 − 1/x2)
  x1, x2 = distances of feet from fault point</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Fault current (A) — from power company records</label><input type="number" id="gpr-i" placeholder="e.g. 5000" oninput="calcGPR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Ground grid resistance (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="gpr-r" placeholder="e.g. 1.2" step="0.1" oninput="calcGPR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Decrement factor (DC offset)</label>
<select id="gpr-df" onchange="calcGPR()">
<option value="1.0">1.0 — conservative (no DC)</option>
<option value="1.15" selected>1.15 — typical substation</option>
<option value="1.25">1.25 — high X/R ratio</option>
</select></div>
<div id="gpr-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>GPR Mitigation Methods</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Method</th><th>Application</th><th>Typical protection</th></tr>
<tr><td>Neutralizing transformer</td><td>Metallic pairs entering GPR zone</td><td>Isolates DC/low-freq, passes voice</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fiber optic cable</td><td>Best solution — no metallic path</td><td>Complete isolation</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gas tube protectors</td><td>Secondary protection on all pairs</td><td>Clamps transients to ground</td></tr>
<tr><td>Shield isolation</td><td>ALPETH / coaxial shield at GPR boundary</td><td>Breaks shield continuity at zone edge</td></tr>
<tr><td>Optical isolator</td><td>T1/data circuits into substation</td><td>Full galvanic isolation, no bandwidth limit</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<div class="eli5"><strong>When is GPR analysis required?</strong><br>
• Any telecom facility within 300 ft of a transmission substation<br>
• Buried cable crossing within 1,000 ft of substation ground mat<br>
• Any cable entering a generating station or industrial substation<br>
• Power company will provide fault current and GPR study data — always request it before installing equipment near a substation.<br><br>
<strong>Key reference:</strong> IEEE Std 487 (Protection of Wire-Line Communication Facilities Serving Electric Power Stations)</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Transfer Voltage -->
<div id="m4-transfer" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Transfer Voltage to Telecom Cable</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> When a GPR event occurs, the elevated ground voltage can "transfer" along the cable shield from the substation area back to the CO. The voltage that arrives at the CO depends on the cable shield resistance, the transfer impedance of the cable, and how far the cable runs through the elevated potential zone.
<div class="mth">Transfer voltage (simplified):
  V_transfer = GPR × (Z_transfer / Z_total)
  
  Z_transfer = transfer impedance of cable in GPR zone
  Z_total    = total cable impedance + ground return

For ALPETH cable (aluminum shield):
  Shield resistance ≈ 0.15 Ω/kft (typical)
  
Conservative estimate — if no detailed study:
  V_transfer ≈ GPR × (L_in_zone / L_total)
  
Where L_in_zone = cable length within GPR zone</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>GPR voltage (V)</label><input type="number" id="tv-gpr" placeholder="e.g. 6000" oninput="calcTV()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable length in GPR zone (feet)</label><input type="number" id="tv-lin" placeholder="e.g. 500" oninput="calcTV()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total cable length to CO (feet)</label><input type="number" id="tv-ltot" placeholder="e.g. 5280" oninput="calcTV()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable type</label>
<select id="tv-type" onchange="calcTV()">
<option value="1.0">Buried ALPETH (aluminum shield)</option>
<option value="0.7">Buried STALPETH (steel + aluminum)</option>
<option value="0.5">Armored cable (heavy steel)</option>
<option value="1.5">Aerial self-support (minimal shielding)</option>
</select></div>
<div id="tv-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="wbox" style="margin-top:8px">This is a simplified estimate. For formal GPR studies, IEEE 487 methodology with actual soil model data and cable parameters should be used. Always consult with your company's power influence engineer for substations with &gt;1,000A fault current.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Transfer Voltage Limits</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Limit</th><th>Value</th><th>Standard</th></tr>
<tr><td>Hazardous touch voltage (OSHA)</td><td>50 Vrms</td><td>OSHA 29 CFR 1910</td></tr>
<tr><td>Hazardous to personnel (IEEE 80)</td><td>Step/touch limits</td><td>IEEE Std 80-2013</td></tr>
<tr><td>CO equipment max exposure</td><td>250V peak</td><td>Telcordia GR-1089</td></tr>
<tr><td>Protector activation (carbon)</td><td>350–500V DC</td><td>AT&T 487</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gas tube activation (3-electrode)</td><td>230–350V DC</td><td>GR-974</td></tr>
<tr><td>NTx required above (telecom)</td><td>300V GPR</td><td>IEEE 487</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">Any GPR event exceeding 300V requires neutralizing transformers on all metallic pairs entering the zone. Any GPR exceeding 5,000V should use fiber optic cable exclusively — no metallic facilities.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- CO Ground Integrity -->
<div id="m4-coground" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>CO Power Room Ground Integrity Check</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The CO ground system is the foundation that everything else depends on. A compromised ground causes noise, equipment damage, and personnel safety hazards. This is a systematic verification procedure.
</div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Master Ground Bar (MGB) to building steel:</strong> Measure with 4-wire milliohm meter. Must be &lt;0.1Ω. Higher resistance means a corroded connection or broken conductor on the MGB-to-steel bond.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Battery return bus to MGB:</strong> Should be &lt;0.01Ω (10 mΩ). The battery return is the current return path for all DC loads — resistance here causes voltage drop that appears as bus voltage variation.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>BDFB frame to MGB:</strong> Should be &lt;0.1Ω. Each BDFB cabinet must have a dedicated ground bond. Verify green/yellow wires are connected, not just looped through the cabinet.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Equipment frame ground to BDFB ground bar:</strong> Any rack or frame with telecom equipment must be bonded. Resistance &lt;0.1Ω. Check that cable tray is also bonded if used as a ground path.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Outside cable sheath ground at main protector frame:</strong> Cable shields must bond to the CO ground at the protector frame. Missing or corroded bonds allow GPR transfer onto equipment.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">6</span><span class="stxt"><strong>AC service entrance ground:</strong> Verify AC system neutral-to-ground bond at main panel. Measure AC ground conductor continuity to MGB. Should be &lt;1Ω.</span></div>
<div class="tip">Document every measurement with the specific location, meter used, date, and technician. Ground system integrity is a life-safety issue — records must be maintained per your company's safety standards.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Ground Resistance Limits Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Point</th><th>Max resistance</th><th>Standard</th></tr>
<tr><td>MGB to earth</td><td>&lt;5 Ω</td><td>GR-1089, NEC 250</td></tr>
<tr><td>MGB to building steel</td><td>&lt;0.1 Ω</td><td>Telcordia</td></tr>
<tr><td>Battery return to MGB</td><td>&lt;10 mΩ</td><td>Company standards</td></tr>
<tr><td>Frame/rack to MGB</td><td>&lt;0.1 Ω</td><td>GR-1089</td></tr>
<tr><td>OSP ground rod (single)</td><td>&lt;25 Ω</td><td>NEC 250.56</td></tr>
<tr><td>OSP ground rod (service area)</td><td>&lt;25 Ω</td><td>Telcordia</td></tr>
<tr><td>Substation telecom ground</td><td>&lt;1 Ω</td><td>IEEE 487</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<div class="eli5"><strong>4-wire (Kelvin) measurement:</strong> Always use 4-wire measurements for resistance below 1Ω. Your test leads have resistance (0.1–0.5Ω each). With 2-wire measurement, you're measuring your lead resistance plus the connection — and the lead resistance alone can exceed the spec. 4-wire drives current through one pair of leads and measures voltage on a separate pair — lead resistance drops out of the measurement.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- −48V Bus Check -->
<div id="m4-bus" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>CO −48V Bus Voltage Check</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The CO bus voltage should be steady at −52 to −54V under normal float conditions. Voltage that's too low means battery discharge or rectifier failure. Too high means rectifier malfunction or over-voltage condition. Voltage that varies with load indicates resistance in the distribution path.
<div class="mth">Check sequence:
  1. Measure at rectifier output bus (+/−)
  2. Measure at BDFB main bus (+/−)
  3. Measure at individual BDFB breaker outputs
  4. Measure at equipment frame (power entry point)

Expected voltage at each point:
  Rectifier output: −52.0 to −54.0V
  BDFB input:       −51.5 to −53.5V  (0.5V drop acceptable)
  Breaker output:   −51.0 to −53.0V  (1.0V total drop acceptable)
  Equipment frame:  −50.5 to −52.5V  (1.5V total drop acceptable)

Voltage drop > 1.5V from rectifier to equipment = investigate!</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Rectifier bus voltage (V, enter as positive)</label><input type="number" id="bus-rect" placeholder="e.g. 53.2" oninput="calcBUS()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>BDFB bus voltage (V)</label><input type="number" id="bus-bdfb" placeholder="e.g. 52.8" oninput="calcBUS()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Equipment frame voltage (V)</label><input type="number" id="bus-eq" placeholder="e.g. 52.1" oninput="calcBUS()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Load current (A) — from shunt</label><input type="number" id="bus-i" placeholder="e.g. 150" oninput="calcBUS()"></div>
<div id="bus-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>−48V Plant Alarm Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Alarm</th><th>Typical threshold</th><th>Action</th></tr>
