<!-- Shield Continuity -->
<div id="m4-shield" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Shield Continuity — ALPETH / STALPETH</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The cable shield (metallic jacket) serves two purposes: moisture barrier and ground path. If the shield is broken, GPR and induced voltages can appear on the conductors inside. Always verify shield continuity end-to-end on any cable suspected of grounding issues.
<div class="mth">Expected shield resistance (Ω):
ALPETH (aluminum shield):
  Shield R ≈ 0.15 Ω/kft (typical)
  
STALPETH (steel + aluminum):
  Shield R ≈ 0.30 Ω/kft (steel layer dominant)
  
Total expected resistance = gauge_resistance × length_kft
If measured &gt; 2× expected: suspect shield damage or poor splice bond</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable type</label>
<select id="sc-type" onchange="calcSC()">
<option value="0.15">ALPETH (aluminum) — 0.15 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="0.30">STALPETH (steel+alum) — 0.30 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="0.08">Coaxial copper shield — 0.08 Ω/kft</option>
<option value="custom">Custom Ω/kft</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field" id="sc-custom-f" style="display:none"><label>Custom shield Ω/kft</label><input type="number" id="sc-cu" oninput="calcSC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="sc-l" placeholder="e.g. 15840" oninput="calcSC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured shield resistance (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="sc-m" placeholder="e.g. 4.8" oninput="calcSC()"></div>
<div id="sc-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Shield Fault Locator — Ratio Arm Method</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> If the shield is faulted (broken and grounded at a point), you can locate it like a Murray loop. Connect a known resistance to the far end shield and measure the ratio.
<div class="mth">Shield fault location:
  d = (R_measured / R_shield_total) × L

Where:
  R_measured     = resistance from your end to fault
  R_shield_total = total shield resistance end-to-end
  L              = one-way cable length</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total shield resistance (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="sf-rt" placeholder="e.g. 4.8" oninput="calcSF()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured resistance to fault (Ω)</label><input type="number" id="sf-rm" placeholder="e.g. 1.9" oninput="calcSF()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="sf-l" placeholder="e.g. 15840" oninput="calcSF()"></div>
<div id="sf-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Shield continuity troubleshooting:</strong><br>
• No continuity at all → splice bond missing, or completely severed shield<br>
• Continuity but very high resistance → corroded splice bond, damaged section<br>
• Intermittent continuity → loose connection at splice, mechanically damaged section<br>
• Shield floating (not grounded at one end) → intentional isolation (check records) or missing ground bond</div>
</div>
