<h3>Shunt mV → Current Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A shunt is a precision low-resistance resistor inserted in the current path. The voltage drop across it is proportional to current — measure the millivolts, know the shunt rating, and you know exactly how many amps are flowing. Every CO battery plant uses this principle.
<div class="mth">I = (V_mV / V_rated_mV) × I_rated_A

Example: 50mV/100A shunt reads 37mV
  I = (37 / 50) × 100 = 74 A

Common shunt ratings:
  50mV/100A   → 1 mV = 2 A
  50mV/200A   → 1 mV = 4 A
  50mV/400A   → 1 mV = 8 A
  50mV/600A   → 1 mV = 12 A
  100mV/100A  → 1 mV = 1 A</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured voltage across shunt (mV)</label><input type="number" id="sh-mv" placeholder="e.g. 37.4" step="0.1" oninput="calcShunt()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Shunt rating</label>
<select id="sh-rat" onchange="calcShunt()">
