<!-- BOD Analysis -->
<div id="m5-bod" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>BOD mV Drop Analysis</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> BOD (Battery/Bus Over-current Distribution) panels distribute −48V power to equipment. Excessive voltage drop across a strap, fuse, breaker, or lug indicates a resistance problem — corroded connection, undersized conductor, or failing component. Measure mV across each component under load to find the culprit.
<div class="mth">Acceptable mV drops (under full load):
  Bus bar strap:     &lt; 5 mV   (at rated current)
  Fuse (good):       &lt; 10 mV  (typical, varies by rating)
  Breaker (good):    &lt; 20 mV  (varies by amp rating)
  Terminal lug:      &lt; 5 mV
  Bus bar section:   &lt; 10 mV  (per section)

Implied resistance = V_drop_mV / (current_A × 1000)
  e.g. 50mV at 100A = 0.5 mΩ (suspect above 0.2 mΩ)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Load current (A)</label><input type="number" id="bod-i" placeholder="e.g. 150" oninput="calcBOD()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Component type</label>
<select id="bod-type" onchange="calcBOD()">
<option value="strap,5">Bus strap — limit 5 mV</option>
<option value="fuse,10">Fuse — limit 10 mV</option>
<option value="breaker,20">Breaker — limit 20 mV</option>
<option value="lug,5">Terminal lug — limit 5 mV</option>
<option value="bar,10">Bus bar section — limit 10 mV</option>
<option value="custom,999">Custom limit</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured mV drop across component</label><input type="number" id="bod-mv" placeholder="e.g. 8.2" step="0.1" oninput="calcBOD()"></div>
<div id="bod-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>BOD Troubleshooting — Where to Measure</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Source bus to load bus:</strong> Measure across the entire BDFB output. Should match the known bus voltage within 0.5V under load.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Breaker input to output:</strong> A good breaker reads &lt;20mV. A failing breaker reads 50mV+. Replace any breaker showing &gt;20% of its rated voltage drop.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Lug to conductor:</strong> Set meter to mV DC. Measure from the lug barrel to the conductor 1 inch away. More than 5mV means the lug is corroded or undertorqued.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Bus strap connections:</strong> Straps that bond parallel bus bars should have near-zero drop. A strap reading 20+ mV is either corroded, loose, or undersized.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Fuse to fuse holder:</strong> Measure across the fuse itself and then across the holder clips separately. A high reading on the holder but not the fuse = corroded holder contacts.</span></div>
<div class="wbox">Always make BOD measurements with the load energized. Resistance problems are load-dependent — a cold joint that reads fine at low current will show high mV at full load.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

