<div id="hdsl-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>HDSL vs T1 Comparison</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Traditional T1</th><th>HDSL/HDSL2</th></tr>
<tr><td>Pairs needed</td><td>1 pair</td><td>2 pairs (HDSL) / 1 pair (HDSL2)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Max reach 24 AWG</td><td>~18,000 ft</td><td>~21,000–24,000 ft</td></tr>
<tr><td>Line code</td><td>AMI / B8ZS</td><td>2B1Q / TC-PAM</td></tr>
<tr><td>Repeaters needed</td><td>Yes (&gt;18 kft)</td><td>No (within reach)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Load coils</td><td>Hard fail</td><td>Hard fail</td></tr>
<tr><td>Bridge taps</td><td>Hard fail (&gt;500ft)</td><td>Hard fail</td></tr>
<tr><td>Provisioning</td><td>DSX cross-connect</td><td>HDSL modem pair at CO + CPE</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>2B1Q Theory — Field Reference</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>2B1Q (Two Binary, One Quaternary)</strong> encodes 2 bits per symbol using 4 voltage levels. This halves the baud rate vs AMI, which is why HDSL can go so much farther — lower baud rate = less attenuation at the line frequency.
<div class="mth">Baud rate = bit rate / 2
  HDSL at 784 kbps each pair → 392 kBaud
  AMI T1 at 1.544 Mbps      → 1.544 MBaud

Lower baud = lower frequency = less cable loss
At 392 kHz vs 1.544 MHz: roughly 2× less attenuation</div></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Pair Gain ID -->
<div id="m5-pairgain" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Pair Gain System Identifier</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Pair gain systems (DLC, SLC-96, GS2000, etc.) carry multiple voice channels over fewer pairs using digital multiplexing. They look like normal pairs from the CO side but behave differently. Identifying pair gain is critical before ordering DSL — most pair gain systems CANNOT support DSL.
</div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Ring test anomaly:</strong> Pair gain lines often ring at a different frequency (25–50 Hz range), may have a "hollow" or "digital" quality, and sometimes ring all lines simultaneously if the system is misconfigured.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Loop current behavior:</strong> Pair gain feeds a synthetic loop. The loop current may be unnaturally steady (digital simulation) rather than varying with load. Check with a loop current meter — synthetic loops often read exactly 20.0 mA.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>TDR test:</strong> A pair gain line shows a TDR reflection at the remote terminal location, then silence. A real pair shows the CPE reflection at the end. The remote terminal will typically show up at a distance corresponding to the feeder cable length.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>DSL modem response:</strong> Pair gain systems typically block DSL frequencies. A DSL modem will fail to train, or will train at very low rates with high errors. If a customer reports DSL worked on their old address but not this one, pair gain is a prime suspect.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Check cable records (ACIS/LFACS):</strong> Pull the cable records. DLC/SLC serving areas are documented. If the serving terminal is more than 18,000 ft away but the customer has service, they're almost certainly on pair gain.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">6</span><span class="stxt"><strong>GS/2 or Subscriber Loop Carrier SLC markings:</strong> Remote terminals are labeled. SLC-96 terminals are gray or beige outdoor cabinets. GS/2 is an AT&T digital pair gain. Any DLC (Digital Loop Carrier) designation means pair gain.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Common Pair Gain Systems</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>System</th><th>Channels</th><th>DSL capable?</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>SLC-96</td><td>96 voice</td><td class="fail">No</td><td>AT&T/Alcatel DLC, most common</td></tr>
<tr><td>GS/2 (Litespan)</td><td>Varies</td><td class="fail">No</td><td>Lucent/AT&T pair gain</td></tr>
<tr><td>DMS-100 DLC</td><td>Varies</td><td class="fail">No</td><td>Nortel DLC</td></tr>
<tr><td>Calix C7 (IDSL only)</td><td>Varies</td><td class="warn">IDSL only</td><td>Some support IDSL, not ADSL</td></tr>
<tr><td>IPDSLAM / FTTN</td><td>Varies</td><td class="pass">Yes</td><td>Fiber-fed DSLAM — DSL works</td></tr>
<tr><td>GPON ONT</td><td>Varies</td><td class="pass">Yes — fiber</td><td>Fiber to the premises — no copper DSL</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="wbox">Never order ADSL2+/VDSL2 on a pair gain line without confirming the terminal supports it. The order will appear to complete, the circuit will fail, and you'll waste a truck roll. Check OSS records first.</div>
</div>
