<!-- Shunt Verification -->
<div id="m6-shuntv" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Live Shunt Verification</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Before trusting any plant controller current reading, verify it against a direct mV measurement. Controllers drift, shunts corrode, and wiring errors happen. A 10% controller error on a 400A plant means you could be 40A off — enough to miss an impending overload.
<div class="mth">Verification steps:
  1. Note controller displayed current (A)
  2. Find the main shunt — usually on the negative bus
  3. Measure mV directly across shunt terminals
  4. Calculate: I = (mV_measured / mV_rated) × A_rated
  5. Compare to controller display
  
Acceptable error: ±3% of shunt rated value
  At 50mV/400A shunt: 3% = ±12A acceptable variation
  &gt;5% error: recalibrate or replace shunt/controller</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Shunt rating (mV)</label><input type="number" id="sv-rmv" placeholder="e.g. 50" oninput="calcSV()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Shunt rating (A)</label><input type="number" id="sv-ra" placeholder="e.g. 400" oninput="calcSV()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured mV across shunt</label><input type="number" id="sv-mv" placeholder="e.g. 22.4" step="0.1" oninput="calcSV()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Controller displayed current (A)</label><input type="number" id="sv-disp" placeholder="e.g. 187" oninput="calcSV()"></div>
<div id="sv-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Shunt Ratio Quick Converter</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Common shunt ratios — find mV/A for any standard shunt.</strong></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Shunt</th><th>Ratio (mV/A)</th><th>Resistance (mΩ)</th><th>At 100A</th><th>At 200A</th></tr>
<tr><td>50mV/100A</td><td>0.500</td><td>0.500</td><td>50.0 mV</td><td>Full scale</td></tr>
<tr><td>50mV/200A</td><td>0.250</td><td>0.250</td><td>25.0 mV</td><td>50.0 mV</td></tr>
<tr><td>50mV/300A</td><td>0.167</td><td>0.167</td><td>16.7 mV</td><td>33.3 mV</td></tr>
<tr><td>50mV/400A</td><td>0.125</td><td>0.125</td><td>12.5 mV</td><td>25.0 mV</td></tr>
<tr><td>50mV/600A</td><td>0.083</td><td>0.083</td><td>8.3 mV</td><td>16.7 mV</td></tr>
<tr><td>50mV/1000A</td><td>0.050</td><td>0.050</td><td>5.0 mV</td><td>10.0 mV</td></tr>
<tr><td>100mV/100A</td><td>1.000</td><td>1.000</td><td>100.0 mV</td><td>Full scale</td></tr>
<tr><td>100mV/200A</td><td>0.500</td><td>0.500</td><td>50.0 mV</td><td>100.0 mV</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">Shunt resistance in mΩ equals the mV rating divided by the A rating. A 50mV/400A shunt has a resistance of 0.125 mΩ. This is why you can't use a regular DMM to measure a shunt directly — you need to read the mV drop under load.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- BDFB Load -->
<div id="m6-bdfb" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>BDFB Total Load vs Main Shunt</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The BDFB (Battery Distribution Fuse Bay) has a main shunt that measures total load, and individual breakers/fuses feeding each equipment bay. The sum of all individual loads should equal the main shunt reading. If there's a significant discrepancy, you have an unmeasured load, a shunt calibration error, or a ground fault.
<div class="mth">Expected: Σ(individual breaker loads) ≈ main shunt load
  Acceptable discrepancy: ±5%
  
  Large discrepancy (>10%) causes:
  • Unmeasured branch circuit
  • Shunt on wrong polarity / wrong bus
  • Ground fault returning current via non-metered path
  • Controller calibration error on main shunt</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Main BDFB shunt reading (A)</label><input type="number" id="bdfb-main" placeholder="e.g. 285" oninput="calcBDFB()"></div>
<div id="bdfb-branches"></div>
<button class="btn" style="max-width:220px;margin-top:6px" onclick="addBDFBBranch()">+ Add Branch Circuit</button>
<div id="bdfb-result" class="result" style="margin-top:10px"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>BDFB Capacity Planning</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>BDFB breakers and buses have maximum current ratings. Plan expansion carefully.</strong>
<div class="mth">BDFB capacity rules of thumb:
  • Never exceed 80% of main breaker rating (NEC 210.20)
  • Each branch breaker: 125% of continuous load (NEC 210.20)
  • Wire from BDFB to equipment: rated for 125% of load
  • Total branch current ≤ main bus rating
  
Typical BDFB ratings:
  Small BDFB:  100A main, 10–20 branch positions
  Medium BDFB: 400A main, 20–40 branch positions
  Large BDFB:  800A–1200A main, 40+ branch positions</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>BDFB main rating (A)</label><input type="number" id="bdfbc-main" placeholder="e.g. 400" oninput="calcBDFBC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Current total load (A)</label><input type="number" id="bdfbc-load" placeholder="e.g. 285" oninput="calcBDFBC()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Planned additional load (A)</label><input type="number" id="bdfbc-add" placeholder="e.g. 60" oninput="calcBDFBC()"></div>
<div id="bdfbc-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
