<div class="card">
<h3>DC → AC Power Conversion — Worked Example</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> You're standing in a CO power room. The plant controller says 300A at −53V. How big is the AC circuit feeding the rectifiers? Here's the complete calculation chain.
<div class="mth">Step 1: DC output power
  P_DC = V_DC × I_DC = 53V × 300A = 15,900 W = 15.9 kW

Step 2: AC input power (accounting for rectifier losses)
  Efficiency = 92% (typical modern rectifier)
  P_AC = P_DC / η = 15,900 / 0.92 = 17,283 W = 17.3 kW

Step 3: AC input apparent power
  Power factor = 0.97 (modern SMPS)
  S_AC = P_AC / PF = 17,283 / 0.97 = 17,817 VA = 17.8 kVA

Step 4: AC current per phase (3-phase 480V)
  I_AC = S_AC / (√3 × V_LL) = 17,817 / (1.732 × 480)
  I_AC = 17,817 / 831.4 = 21.4 A per phase

Step 5: NEC 125% continuous load rule
  I_breaker_min = 21.4 × 1.25 = 26.8 A
  → Select next standard size: 30A breaker
  → Wire: 10 AWG copper at 75°C (30A rated)</div></div>
