<!-- Fresnel / Earth Bulge -->
<div id="m7-fresnel" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Fresnel Zone Radius</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Radio waves don't travel in a perfectly straight line — they spread slightly. The first Fresnel zone is an ellipsoid around the direct path. If 60% of this zone is clear of obstacles, the link performs as if the path were totally clear. Anything inside the 60% clearance zone causes diffraction loss.
<div class="mth">Fresnel zone radius at point x along path:
  r1 = 17.3 × √(d1 × d2 / (f × d))  (meters)
  
  d1 = distance from Tx to obstacle (km)
  d2 = distance from obstacle to Rx (km)
  d  = total path length (km)
  f  = frequency (GHz)

Required clearance = 0.6 × r1 (60% of 1st zone)

Max first Fresnel zone radius (at path midpoint):
  r1_max = 8.66 × √(d / f)
  d in km, f in GHz, r1 in meters</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Frequency (GHz)</label><input type="number" id="fz-f" placeholder="e.g. 6" step="0.1" oninput="calcFZ()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total path length (miles)</label><input type="number" id="fz-d" placeholder="e.g. 20" oninput="calcFZ()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Distance from Tx to obstacle (miles)</label><input type="number" id="fz-d1" placeholder="e.g. 10" oninput="calcFZ()"></div>
<div id="fz-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Earth Bulge Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The Earth curves away from a straight line between two antennas. At long distances, this "bulge" can block a signal even when you can't see any obstacles. The effective bulge depends on the K-factor — how much the atmosphere bends the signal downward (which partially compensates for Earth curvature).
<div class="mth">Earth bulge at point x along path:
  h = (d1 × d2) / (12.74 × K)  (meters)
  
  d1, d2 = distances from each end to point (km)
  K = effective Earth radius factor
      K=4/3 (1.333) = standard atmosphere
      K=1.0 = no refraction (worst case for bulge)
      K=2/3 = sub-refraction (ducting conditions)

Max bulge (at midpoint of path d km long):
  h_max = d² / (50.96 × K)  meters</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total path length (miles)</label><input type="number" id="eb-d" placeholder="e.g. 20" oninput="calcEB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Distance from Tx to midpoint (miles) — leave blank for path midpoint</label><input type="number" id="eb-d1" placeholder="optional" oninput="calcEB()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>K-factor</label>
<select id="eb-k" onchange="calcEB()">
<option value="1.333" selected>K = 4/3 (1.333) — standard atmosphere</option>
<option value="1.0">K = 1.0 — worst case (no refraction)</option>
<option value="0.667">K = 2/3 (0.667) — sub-refraction</option>
<option value="2.0">K = 2.0 — super-refraction</option>
</select></div>
<div id="eb-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Rain Fade -->
<div id="m7-rain" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Rain Fade — ITU-R P.838</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Rain absorbs and scatters microwave signals. The higher the frequency, the worse the rain attenuation. At 6 GHz, rain is barely a problem. At 38 GHz, a heavy rainstorm can knock out a link that looks perfectly healthy in clear weather.
<div class="mth">Rain attenuation:
  A = γ_R × r_eff   (dB)
  
  γ_R = specific attenuation (dB/km)
      = k × R^α    (ITU-R P.838)
  R   = rain rate (mm/hr)
  r_eff = effective path length (km)
        ≈ path_length / (1 + path_length/35)

Approximate k and α (horizontal polarization):
  6 GHz:  k≈0.00155, α≈1.265
  11 GHz: k≈0.0188,  α≈1.217
  18 GHz: k≈0.101,   α≈1.060
  23 GHz: k≈0.187,   α≈1.000
  38 GHz: k≈0.600,   α≈0.890

Rain rate zones (ITU-R P.837):
  Zone E (SE USA): 22 mm/hr for 0.01% of year
  Zone K (heavy): 42 mm/hr for 0.01% of year</div></div>
