<!-- Field Diagnosis -->
<div id="m7-faultdiag" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Common Microwave Faults — Field Diagnosis</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause</th><th>First check</th></tr>
<tr><td>RSL suddenly drops 20+ dB</td><td>Antenna misalignment (wind, ice, vandalism)</td><td>Check antenna mount, look for physical shift</td></tr>
<tr><td>RSL low but stable</td><td>Antenna misalignment, wrong polarization, waveguide damaged</td><td>Verify polarization, sweep antenna alignment</td></tr>
<tr><td>RSL drops during rain</td><td>Rain fade (expected above 18 GHz), or water in waveguide flange</td><td>Check frequency — below 11 GHz? Probably waveguide moisture</td></tr>
<tr><td>RSL drops at same time daily</td><td>Solar-induced multipath (sunrise/sunset), thermal expansion of tower</td><td>Log RSL vs time — pattern reveals thermal/atmospheric</td></tr>
<tr><td>Intermittent errors, RSL fine</td><td>Interference from co-channel source, oscillator phase noise</td><td>Spectrum analyzer on receive frequency, check for new neighbors</td></tr>
<tr><td>High BER, RSL good</td><td>Wrong modulation/framing, clock mismatch, LBO, cable problem at DSX</td><td>Verify framing (ESF/D4), check BER end-to-end with BERT</td></tr>
<tr><td>No signal at all</td><td>Power failure, LOS software down, cable unplugged</td><td>Check power LEDs, management port, then physical RF connectors</td></tr>
<tr><td>Link bouncing (up/down)</td><td>Intermittent power, loose connector, near-threshold RSL with multipath</td><td>Check RSL during outage window — below threshold = propagation; at threshold = marginal path</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Microwave Alignment Procedure</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Verify both ends powered and licensed:</strong> Confirm TX power on, operating frequency correct, polarization matches coordination documents.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Coarse alignment:</strong> Use compass bearing from link design documents. Aim dish within ±5° of calculated azimuth. Confirm visual LOS with binoculars if distance allows.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Fine alignment with RSL meter:</strong> Slowly sweep azimuth while monitoring RSL. Find peak. Then sweep elevation. Peak RSL = main beam aligned. Note: a "false peak" at sidelobe is possible — the main beam peak will be significantly higher (3–6 dB above any sidelobe).</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Lock mount and re-verify:</strong> After tightening mount bolts, RSL often shifts slightly. Re-verify RSL after final torque. Some antennas have fine-adjust screws — use them before final torque.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Compare to design RSL:</strong> Achieved RSL should be within ±3 dB of the link budget prediction. More than 5 dB below design suggests a problem — waveguide not seated, wrong antenna, obstruction in path.</span></div>
<div class="tip">Coordinate both ends simultaneously via radio or phone — far-end alignment also affects RSL at the near end. Single-ended alignment misses polarization and pointing errors at the far end.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

