<!-- Seismic -->
<div id="m9-seismic" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>NEBS Seismic Zones (GR-63)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> NEBS defines seismic zones based on geographic location. Equipment must be designed and installed to withstand the seismic forces for the zone where it will be installed. Zone 4 (California, Pacific Northwest) has the strictest requirements.
</div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Zone</th><th>Description</th><th>Geographic areas</th><th>Peak ground accel.</th></tr>
<tr><td>Zone 0</td><td>No seismic requirement</td><td>Stable interior US, Canada</td><td>&lt;0.05g</td></tr>
<tr><td>Zone 1</td><td>Minor seismic</td><td>Central/Eastern US, most of Canada</td><td>0.05–0.18g</td></tr>
<tr><td>Zone 2</td><td>Moderate seismic</td><td>Parts of Midwest, Southeast US</td><td>0.18–0.25g</td></tr>
<tr><td>Zone 3</td><td>Strong seismic</td><td>Pacific NW, parts of Mountain West</td><td>0.25–0.40g</td></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>Zone 4</td><td>Very strong seismic</td><td>California, Pacific coast, Alaska, Hawaii</td><td>&gt;0.40g</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Seismic Anchoring Requirements</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Floor anchoring:</strong> All equipment racks and frames must be bolted to the floor with anchor bolts sized for the seismic zone. Zone 4 requires seismic-rated anchor bolts tested to the required g-force.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Top bracing / anti-tip:</strong> Racks taller than 4:1 (height:width ratio) require top bracing. Most 7-ft telecom racks need top ties to the ceiling frame or adjacent racks.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Battery rack anchoring:</strong> Battery racks have special requirements. The combined weight × seismic force can exceed 1g. IEEE 1188 and GR-63 both require calculation of seismic forces for battery installations.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Cable management:</strong> In Zone 3/4, cables must be bundled and restrained to prevent whipping during a seismic event. Overhead cable trays must have seismic hangers.</span></div>
<div class="wbox">NEBS seismic compliance requires formal documentation and, in Zone 3/4, third-party testing or analysis certification for the equipment. Check your equipment's GR-63 compliance certificate for zone rating.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Seismic Force Calculator (Simplified)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Estimate the horizontal seismic force on a piece of equipment to verify anchor bolt requirements.</strong>
<div class="mth">F_seismic = W × a_peak_g × I_factor
  W        = equipment weight (lbs)
  a_peak_g = peak ground acceleration (g)
  I_factor = importance factor (1.5 for critical telecom)

Force is applied horizontally at the equipment's
center of mass. Overturning moment = F × h_cm.</div></div>
