<!-- Fire Suppression -->
<div id="m9-fire" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Fire Suppression Reference</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>CO and data rooms use specialized fire suppression — NOT water sprinklers — because water destroys electronic equipment. Understanding the system in your facility is a safety requirement before working in any suppressed space.</strong></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Agent</th><th>Type</th><th>How it works</th><th>Safe for occupied space?</th></tr>
<tr><td>FM-200 (HFC-227ea)</td><td>Clean agent gas</td><td>Absorbs heat, interrupts combustion</td><td class="pass">Yes — NFPA 2001 compliant</td></tr>
<tr><td>Novec 1230</td><td>Clean agent gas</td><td>Absorbs heat, low GWP</td><td class="pass">Yes — low toxicity</td></tr>
<tr><td>CO₂ (total flooding)</td><td>Inert gas</td><td>Displaces oxygen</td><td class="fail">NO — lethal in high concentration</td></tr>
<tr><td>Halon 1301 (legacy)</td><td>Halogenated gas</td><td>Chemical suppression</td><td class="warn">Yes at design conc. but phased out</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inergen / IG-541</td><td>Inert gas blend</td><td>Reduces O₂ to ~12.5%</td><td class="warn">Yes at design — confirm O₂ level</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pre-action sprinkler</td><td>Water — 2-stage</td><td>Requires detector + flow signal</td><td class="pass">Yes — used in some CO areas</td></tr>
<tr><td>VESDA (early warning)</td><td>Detection only</td><td>Aspirating smoke detection</td><td class="pass">Detection only — no agent</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Before Working in a Suppressed Space</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn red">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Identify the suppression agent:</strong> Check the placard on the suppression panel or door. CO₂ requires immediate evacuation if discharge occurs — it is lethal at suppression concentrations.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn red">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Know the pre-discharge warning:</strong> Most systems have a 30–60 second pre-alarm before discharge. This is your evacuation window. Know where the exits are before you start work.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn red">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Manual abort procedure:</strong> Know where the abort switch is and what it does. Most systems allow a brief abort window. After discharge begins, you cannot stop it.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>After discharge:</strong> Do not re-enter until the room has been ventilated and cleared by authorized personnel. Check O₂ level with a gas meter before re-entry, especially after CO₂ or inert gas discharge.</span></div>
</div>
