<!-- TDR -->
<div id="m10-tdr" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>TDR Distance to Fault</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A TDR sends a pulse and measures how long the reflection takes to return. Distance = (speed × time) / 2. The speed depends on the cable's Velocity of Propagation (VoP), which is a percentage of the speed of light.
<div class="mth">d = (VoP × c × t) / 2
  VoP = velocity of propagation (decimal, e.g. 0.67)
  c   = 983,571,056 ft/s (speed of light in feet)
  t   = round-trip time (nanoseconds)

Or from TDR distance reading with wrong VoP:
  d_true = d_displayed × (VoP_true / VoP_used)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Round-trip time (ns) — from TDR</label><input type="number" id="tdr-t" placeholder="e.g. 125" step="0.1" oninput="calcTDR()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable type / VoP</label>
<select id="tdr-vop" onchange="tdrVopChange()">
<option value="0.67">Twisted pair (PIC) — 0.67</option>
<option value="0.69">Twisted pair (PASP/pulp) — 0.69</option>
<option value="0.66">Cat5e/6 UTP — 0.66</option>
<option value="0.78">Coax RG-6 — 0.78</option>
<option value="0.82">Coax RG-11 — 0.82</option>
<option value="0.85">LMR-400 coax — 0.85</option>
<option value="0.695">Fiber (SMF, IOR 1.4677) — 0.695</option>
<option value="custom">Custom VoP</option>
</select></div>
<div id="tdr-custom-f" style="display:none">
<div class="field"><label>Custom VoP (0.50–0.99)</label><input type="number" id="tdr-vop-c" placeholder="e.g. 0.72" step="0.001" oninput="calcTDR()"></div>
</div>
<div id="tdr-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>VoP Calibration</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>If you know the true length of a cable, back-calculate VoP from the TDR reading.</strong></div>
<div class="field"><label>Known cable length (feet)</label><input type="number" id="tdr-kl" placeholder="e.g. 10000" oninput="calcVoP()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>TDR displayed distance (feet)</label><input type="number" id="tdr-disp" placeholder="e.g. 9650" oninput="calcVoP()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>VoP used by TDR for that reading</label><input type="number" id="tdr-vop-used" placeholder="e.g. 0.67" step="0.001" oninput="calcVoP()"></div>
<div id="vop-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>TDR Waveform Fault Identification</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Waveform signature</th><th>Fault type</th><th>Next step</th></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>Positive reflection spike</td><td>Open circuit (break, corroded terminal)</td><td>Murray loop or capacitance test to confirm distance</td></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>Negative reflection dip</td><td>Short circuit (ground fault, wet splice)</td><td>Murray loop to confirm; locate splice</td></tr>
<tr><td>Small positive bump</td><td>Bridge tap / stub cable</td><td>Locate and remove tap before DSL</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gradual slope change</td><td>Impedance change (gauge change, loading)</td><td>Note distance — may be normal splice point</td></tr>
<tr><td>Multiple reflections</td><td>Multiple faults or mismatched impedances</td><td>Resolve nearest fault first, then re-test</td></tr>
<tr><td>Noise / no clear pulse</td><td>Active pair (pair in service), too short</td><td>Test from idle pair; use shorter pulse width</td></tr>
<tr><td>Reflection at expected length, then open</td><td>Normal end of cable — no fault</td><td>Fault may be on wrong pair — re-tone</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">TDR dead zone: the pulse width determines the minimum detectable distance. A 10 ns pulse has a ~5 ft dead zone. Use shorter pulse widths for near-end faults and longer pulse widths for long cables (better signal, longer dead zone).</div>
</div>
