<h3>−48V DC Plant Arc Flash</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Good news for CO techs: −48V DC systems have very low arc flash energy compared to AC systems.</strong>
<div class="mth">−48V DC arc flash characteristics:
  • Arcs at 48V DC are difficult to sustain
  • Energy is typically &lt;1 cal/cm² at typical SCC levels
  • Burns are still possible from short circuits
  • Primary hazard is copper splatter and flash burn, not sustained arc
  
NFPA 70E for −48V DC:
  Incident energy analysis often shows Cat 1 or below
  Minimum PPE: safety glasses, insulated gloves
  No metal jewelry, watches, rings
  
The real risk at 48V is NOT arc flash — it's:
  • Short circuit current heating conductors
  • Copper splatter from fuse/breaker operation  
  • Battery explosion from overcharge/short
  • H₂ gas ignition in battery rooms</div></div>
<div class="tip">For CO −48V work: safety glasses + insulated gloves is minimum. Face shield recommended when working near exposed bus. The arc flash risk is low but the short-circuit current risk is real — a 400 Ah battery can deliver thousands of amps into a dead short.</div>
