<h3>Neutralizing Transformer Sizing</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A neutralizing transformer (NTx) is installed on metallic cable pairs entering a GPR zone to block the low-frequency common-mode voltage while passing voice and data signals. It must be sized to handle the peak GPR voltage without saturating.
<div class="mth">NTx sizing parameters:
  1. GPR voltage (from power company study)
  2. Longitudinal current = GPR / Zshield
  3. NTx turns ratio for required isolation
  
Rule of thumb:
  Voltage rating ≥ peak GPR × 1.5 safety factor
  Current rating ≥ calculated longitudinal current
  Bandwidth: NTx passes ~300–3400 Hz voice; data
             requires wideband NTx (8 Hz–1 MHz)

Common NTx ratings:
  Voice grade: 600V, 1A longitudinal
  T1 capable:  600V, 2A, wideband
  High voltage: 2,500V–15,000V for major substations</div></div>
