<!-- Power Factor -->
<div id="m10-pf" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Power Factor Correction (kVAR)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Power factor is how efficiently your electrical system is using the power supplied. A PF of 0.8 means you're drawing 25% more current from the utility than your equipment actually needs. Correcting PF with capacitor banks reduces your utility bill, lowers current, and reduces conductor heating.
<div class="mth">kVAR needed to correct from PF1 to PF2:
  Q = P × (tan(θ1) − tan(θ2))
  θ = arccos(PF)
  P = real power (kW)
  Q = reactive power needed (kVAR)

kVA, kW, kVAR triangle:
  kVA² = kW² + kVAR²
  PF   = kW / kVA = cos(θ)
  kVAR = kVA × sin(θ)
  kW   = kVA × cos(θ)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Real power load (kW)</label><input type="number" id="pf-kw" placeholder="e.g. 100" oninput="calcPF()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Current power factor</label><input type="number" id="pf-pf1" placeholder="e.g. 0.75" step="0.01" min="0.1" max="1.0" oninput="calcPF()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Target power factor</label><input type="number" id="pf-pf2" value="0.95" step="0.01" min="0.5" max="1.0" oninput="calcPF()"></div>
<div id="pf-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Power Factor Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>PF</th><th>Meaning</th><th>kVA vs kW</th></tr>
<tr><td>1.0</td><td>Unity — perfect</td><td>kVA = kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.97</td><td>Modern SMPS rectifiers</td><td>kVA = 1.03 × kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.95</td><td>Good — typical target</td><td>kVA = 1.05 × kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.90</td><td>Acceptable — light motors</td><td>kVA = 1.11 × kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.85</td><td>Marginal — generator sizing PF</td><td>kVA = 1.18 × kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.80</td><td>Poor — heavily inductive loads</td><td>kVA = 1.25 × kW</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.70</td><td>Bad — unloaded transformers, old motors</td><td>kVA = 1.43 × kW</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">Utility penalties for poor power factor typically kick in below 0.85–0.90 PF. Capacitor banks at the service entrance are the most economical correction for large facilities. Individual motor capacitors are used for large motor loads.</div>
