<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A tower ground ring is a buried copper conductor encircling the base of a tower. Combined with ground rods, it creates a low-impedance earth connection for lightning and fault current. The ring must be large enough to provide adequate earth contact.
<div class="mth">Ground ring resistance (simplified Dwight):
  R_ring = (ρ / (2π² × r)) × ln(2r/a)
  
  ρ = soil resistivity (Ω·cm)
  r = ring radius (cm)
  a = conductor radius (cm)
  
  For 2/0 AWG bare copper (a ≈ 0.275 cm):
  Combined ring + rods reduces overall resistance
  
IEEE recommended: R ≤ 10Ω for tower base ground
TIA-222: ≤ 25Ω for antenna structure ground</div></div>
