<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> Gas tube protectors (GTPs) are 3-electrode gas discharge tubes installed at the protector frame. When a transient exceeds the tube's breakdown voltage, it fires — shorting tip and ring to ground and clamping the voltage. They're the primary lightning/surge protection for CO cable entries.
</div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Standard GTP</th><th>High-voltage GTP</th></tr>
<tr><td>DC breakdown voltage</td><td>230V or 350V</td><td>470V or 600V</td></tr>
<tr><td>Impulse breakdown (10×1000µs)</td><td>±600–800V</td><td>±800–1000V</td></tr>
<tr><td>Discharge current (8×20µs)</td><td>20 kA</td><td>20 kA</td></tr>
<tr><td>Insertion loss</td><td>&lt;0.5 dB</td><td>&lt;0.5 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Capacitance</td><td>&lt;3 pF</td><td>&lt;3 pF</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Protector Selection Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Application</th><th>Protector type</th><th>Breakdown voltage</th></tr>
<tr><td>Standard POTS / voice</td><td>Gas tube + heat coil</td><td>230V (3-electrode)</td></tr>
<tr><td>DSL coexisting with POTS</td><td>Wideband gas tube</td><td>230V, low capacitance</td></tr>
<tr><td>T1 / data circuits</td><td>3-electrode or solid state</td><td>350V typical</td></tr>
<tr><td>GPR exposure area</td><td>High-voltage gas tube</td><td>470V or 600V</td></tr>
<tr><td>Direct buried cable entry</td><td>Heat coil + gas tube</td><td>Per pair voltage</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="wbox">A failed gas tube that has fired and remained in the shorted position looks like a ground fault on the pair. Always test protectors individually with a high-voltage DC tester before blaming the cable. A shorted tube reads like a 0–50Ω fault to ground on T-G and R-G.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Protector Failure Modes</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Reading</th><th>Tube condition</th><th>Action</th></tr>
<tr><td>Open circuit (∞Ω) tip and ring to ground</td><td>Normal — tube not fired</td><td>No action needed</td></tr>
<tr><td>0–50Ω to ground on T or R</td><td>Tube shorted (fired and stuck)</td><td>Replace protector module</td></tr>
<tr><td>50–1000Ω to ground</td><td>Partial discharge / contamination</td><td>Replace protector, check for moisture</td></tr>
<tr><td>Very low IR on one conductor only</td><td>Suspect protector before cable</td><td>Remove protectors, re-test pair</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">When troubleshooting apparent ground faults: always unplug or remove the protectors and re-test the pair. A shorted GTP is one of the most commonly missed causes of "cable ground faults" — and one of the quickest fixes.</div>
</div>
