<!-- How It Works -->
<div id="m11-how" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>How OTDR Works</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> An OTDR is like a bat using echolocation — it sends a short burst of laser light into the fiber and listens for what bounces back. Two things bounce back: Rayleigh backscatter (continuous weak reflection along the whole fiber) and Fresnel reflections (strong reflections from connectors, breaks, and the fiber end).
<div class="mth">Rayleigh backscatter:
  Caused by microscopic density variations in glass
  Creates the characteristic downward-sloping trace
  Slope = fiber attenuation (dB/km)
  Steeper slope = more lossy fiber

Fresnel reflection:
  Caused by refractive index change at an interface
  (air gap, cleaved end, connector, mechanical splice)
  Appears as a spike UP on the trace
  Return loss = how much light bounces back

Distance calculation:
  d = (VoP × c × t) / 2
  VoP = c_fiber / c_vacuum = 1/IOR
  t   = round-trip travel time</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>OTDR Physics — Field Intuition</h3>
<div class="eli5">
<strong>Why the trace slopes downward:</strong> As the pulse travels farther, it gets weaker (attenuation). The backscattered light from farther points is also weaker. So the trace level drops continuously — the slope of this drop is the fiber's attenuation in dB/km.<br><br>
<strong>Why connectors show as spikes:</strong> At an air gap between two fibers (like inside a connector), there's a sudden change from glass (IOR ~1.47) to air (IOR=1.0) and back. This mismatch reflects a lot of light — visible as a sharp upward spike.<br><br>
<strong>Why fusion splices show as dips (not spikes):</strong> A good fusion splice has no air gap, so no Fresnel reflection. Only a small amount of loss occurs from mode-field diameter mismatch or misalignment — seen as a tiny step down on the trace, no spike.<br><br>
<strong>Why you measure from both ends:</strong> IOR mismatch between the two fiber segments at a splice creates a measurement artifact — the splice looks different from each direction. Averaging both measurements gives the true physical loss.
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Trace Anatomy -->
<div id="m11-anatomy" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>OTDR Trace Anatomy</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Trace feature</th><th>What it represents</th><th>Key measurement</th></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>Launch spike (at 0 m)</td><td>Fresnel reflection at OTDR port / launch cable near end</td><td>Start of measurable fiber — end of dead zone</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sloping backscatter line</td><td>Normal fiber loss along the span</td><td>Slope = attenuation (dB/km) — should match fiber spec</td></tr>
<tr><td>Step down (no spike)</td><td>Fusion splice loss or macrobend loss</td><td>Height of step = splice loss in dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Spike up then step down</td><td>Mechanical splice or connector (with air gap)</td><td>Spike height = return loss; step = insertion loss</td></tr>
<tr><td>Large spike then silence</td><td>Cleaved end of fiber or complete break with air gap</td><td>Distance to spike = fiber length or break distance</td></tr>
<tr><td>Spike with no step</td><td>Connector with near-zero insertion loss (rare)</td><td>Good connector — verify both ends</td></tr>
<tr><td>Step down with no spike</td><td>Macrobend, crush, or fusion splice</td><td>Monitor — if step increases over time, active degradation</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gradual slope change</td><td>Different fiber type or elevated temperature section</td><td>Note location — may be outdoor vs indoor section</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ghost echo (second spike)</td><td>Strong reflection bouncing back and forth</td><td>Appears at 2× the reflection distance — see Ghost tab</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Reading a Trace — Step by Step</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Verify the launch:</strong> The trace should start cleanly after the launch cable. If the OTDR port itself is dirty, you'll see a huge spike and noisy trace from the start. Clean before measuring.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Check the slope:</strong> The overall backscatter slope should match the fiber's rated attenuation. At 1310nm, SMF should be about 0.33 dB/km. Steeper = more loss (bend, damage, wrong fiber type).</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Identify all events:</strong> Mark each spike and step. Note the distance and loss for each. Compare to your splice/connector log — every event should be accounted for.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Measure the end reflection:</strong> The fiber end shows as the last spike. Its distance is the fiber length. If there's no spike at the end, the fiber may be broken or very well angle-cleaved.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Compare to link budget:</strong> Total end-to-end loss = launch spike level − noise floor level. Should match your link budget ± a few tenths of dB.</span></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Event Types -->
<div id="m11-events" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Reflective Events (Connector / Break)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Anything with an air gap creates a Fresnel reflection — a spike up on the trace.</strong></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Event</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Typical return loss</th><th>Typical insertion loss</th></tr>
<tr><td>PC/UPC connector (clean)</td><td>Spike + small step</td><td>45–55 dB</td><td>0.2–0.5 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>APC connector (clean)</td><td>Very small spike + small step</td><td>60–70 dB</td><td>0.2–0.5 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Dirty connector</td><td>Spike + larger step</td><td>20–40 dB</td><td>0.5–3 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mechanical splice (air gap)</td><td>Spike + step</td><td>30–45 dB</td><td>0.1–0.5 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fiber break (clean cleave)</td><td>Large spike, then noise</td><td>&gt;40 dB</td><td>Total loss</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fiber break (rough fracture)</td><td>Large spike, then noise</td><td>20–35 dB</td><td>Total loss</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Non-Reflective Events (Splice / Bend)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>No air gap = no Fresnel spike. These show as steps down only.</strong></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Event</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Typical loss</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>Fusion splice (good)</td><td>Small step down, no spike</td><td>0.01–0.1 dB</td><td>Accept ≤0.1 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fusion splice (poor)</td><td>Larger step down</td><td>0.1–0.5 dB</td><td>Re-splice if &gt;0.3 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Macrobend</td><td>Step down, no spike</td><td>0.1–5 dB</td><td>Increases over time; fix bend</td></tr>
<tr><td>Microbend / crush</td><td>Step down, no spike</td><td>Variable</td><td>Often cable damage; may worsen</td></tr>
<tr><td>Gainer splice (artifact)</td><td>Step UP, no spike</td><td>Apparent gain</td><td>Not real — IOR mismatch artifact; see Gainer tab</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">A step UP with no spike is always a gainer artifact — fibers don't amplify. The true loss is the average of the two bidirectional measurements. Never report a gainer as "negative loss" — document it as an artifact and record the averaged value.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Distance / IOR -->
<div id="m11-dist" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>OTDR Distance Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> OTDR distance is based on travel time of light. The IOR (Index of Refraction) tells you how much slower light travels in fiber vs vacuum. Wrong IOR = wrong distance. Always match IOR to your specific fiber type.
<div class="mth">d = (c × t) / (2 × IOR)
  c   = 299,792,458 m/s
  t   = round-trip time (nanoseconds)
  IOR = index of refraction

Or from OTDR reading with wrong IOR:
  d_true = d_displayed × (IOR_used / IOR_true)</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Round-trip time (ns) — from OTDR</label><input type="number" id="ot-t" placeholder="e.g. 97.4" step="0.01" oninput="calcOT()"></div>
