<div class="eli5"><strong>Why does IOR matter so much?</strong><br>
A difference of just 0.001 in IOR causes a 0.068% distance error. On a 10 km span that's 6.8 meters — enough to put a fusion splice location off by two or three splice cases in the field. Always get the IOR from the cable manufacturer's data sheet for the specific cable reel installed.
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Dead Zones -->
<div id="m11-deadzone" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Dead Zone Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> After the OTDR fires a pulse, the detector is blinded for a short time by the large reflection. This is the dead zone — you can't see events that happen during this window. Two types: Event Dead Zone (EDZ) and Attenuation Dead Zone (ADZ). EDZ is shorter; ADZ is longer.
<div class="mth">Event Dead Zone (EDZ):
  Minimum distance between two resolvable reflective events
  EDZ ≈ pulse_width_ns × VoP × c / 2
  Typically 1–10 m for short pulse widths

Attenuation Dead Zone (ADZ):
  Distance after a reflective event before you can
  accurately measure the backscatter level again
  ADZ ≈ 3–5× EDZ
  Typically 5–50 m

Reducing dead zones: use shorter pulse width
  Trade-off: shorter pulse = more noise on long spans</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Pulse width (ns)</label>
<select id="dz-pw" onchange="calcDZ()">
<option value="5">5 ns (shortest — best dead zone)</option>
<option value="10" selected>10 ns (typical short-haul)</option>
<option value="30">30 ns</option>
<option value="100">100 ns</option>
<option value="275">275 ns</option>
<option value="1000">1 µs (1000 ns — long haul)</option>
</select></div>
<div class="field"><label>Fiber IOR</label><input type="number" id="dz-ior" value="1.4677" step="0.0001" oninput="calcDZ()"></div>
<div id="dz-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Pulse Width Selection Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Pulse width</th><th>Best for</th><th>Dead zone (approx)</th><th>Max range</th></tr>
<tr><td>5–10 ns</td><td>Near-end events, connector inspection</td><td>1–3 m</td><td>~5 km</td></tr>
<tr><td>30–100 ns</td><td>Short links, data center fiber</td><td>3–15 m</td><td>~20 km</td></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>100–275 ns</td><td>Metro rings, typical OSP spans</td><td>15–40 m</td><td>~80 km</td></tr>
<tr><td>500 ns – 1 µs</td><td>Long-haul, submarine feeder</td><td>75–150 m</td><td>~200 km</td></tr>
<tr><td>4–10 µs</td><td>Ultra-long haul with high launch power</td><td>600 m+</td><td>~400 km</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">When testing a buried span with splices close together, always take two traces: one short pulse width (to see near-end events clearly) and one long pulse width (to see the full span). Save both — they complement each other.</div>
</div>
