<!-- Launch Cable -->
<div id="m11-launch" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Launch Cable Selection</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The OTDR's own port connector creates a dead zone — you can't see events right at the start of the fiber under test. A launch cable (also called a launch spool or mandrel) is a known-good fiber spool that you connect between the OTDR and the cable under test. It moves the dead zone back before the cable you're testing, so you can see the first connector/splice clearly.
<div class="mth">Launch cable requirements:
  Length ≥ ADZ of the OTDR at your test settings
  Typically 50–200 m for most field OTDRs
  Same fiber type as cable under test (SMF or MMF)
  Both connectors must be clean and low-loss

Launch cable also lets you measure:
  - Loss of the FIRST connector on the cable under test
  - Events within the first few hundred meters

Without launch cable:
  - First 10–50 m is in the dead zone
  - Near-end connector loss is UNMEASURABLE</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>OTDR ADZ at your pulse width (m)</label><input type="number" id="lc-adz" placeholder="e.g. 30" oninput="calcLaunch()"></div>
<div id="lc-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Launch Cable Length Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Pulse width</th><th>Min launch cable</th><th>Recommended</th></tr>
<tr><td>10 ns</td><td>15 m</td><td>50 m</td></tr>
<tr><td>30 ns</td><td>25 m</td><td>75 m</td></tr>
<tr><td>100 ns</td><td>50 m</td><td>100 m</td></tr>
<tr><td>275 ns</td><td>100 m</td><td>200 m</td></tr>
<tr><td>1 µs</td><td>300 m</td><td>500 m</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Tail Cable (Receive End)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>A tail cable at the far end lets you measure the LAST connector loss on the link.</strong><br><br>
Without a tail cable, the last connector loss is hidden in the end-of-fiber dead zone — the Fresnel reflection from the connector masks the loss measurement just before it. A 50–200 m tail cable at the far end brings this event into the measurable region.<br><br>
<strong>Full professional OTDR measurement:</strong><br>
Launch cable → Cable under test → Tail cable<br>
Then reverse: test from the far end with the same setup.<br>
Average all splice/connector results for true loss values.
</div>
<div class="tip">For acceptance testing of new cable installations, most contractor standards require bidirectional OTDR traces with launch AND tail cables. A single-ended trace without launch/tail cables does not meet professional acceptance test standards.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Splice Loss -->
<div id="m11-spliceloss" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Splice Loss — Two-Cursor Method</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> To measure splice loss accurately, place cursor A on the backscatter line just BEFORE the event, and cursor B on the backscatter line just AFTER the event. The vertical difference between the two cursor levels is the splice loss.
<div class="mth">Splice loss = Level_before − Level_after  (dB)

Cursor placement rules:
  Cursor A: on backscatter slope, ≥2× dead zone BEFORE event
  Cursor B: on backscatter slope, ≥2× dead zone AFTER event
  Both cursors must be on the LINEAR backscatter
  (not in the noise floor, not in an artifact region)

Common mistakes:
  - Cursor A too close to event: reads low (dead zone)
  - Cursor B too close to event: reads high (tail artifact)
  - Cursors on noisy section: unreliable reading</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Backscatter level before event (dB)</label><input type="number" id="sl-before" placeholder="e.g. -12.4" step="0.01" oninput="calcSL()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Backscatter level after event (dB)</label><input type="number" id="sl-after" placeholder="e.g. -12.7" step="0.01" oninput="calcSL()"></div>
<div id="sl-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Splice Loss Acceptance Thresholds</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Splice type</th><th>Excellent</th><th>Acceptable</th><th>Reject</th></tr>
<tr><td>Fusion splice (SM)</td><td>≤0.05 dB</td><td>≤0.1 dB</td><td>&gt;0.3 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fusion splice (MM)</td><td>≤0.1 dB</td><td>≤0.3 dB</td><td>&gt;0.5 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mechanical splice</td><td>≤0.1 dB</td><td>≤0.3 dB</td><td>&gt;0.5 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>Connector (new)</td><td>≤0.3 dB</td><td>≤0.5 dB</td><td>&gt;0.75 dB</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Loss Measurement — Bidirectional Averaging</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Why average both directions:</strong> When two fiber segments have slightly different mode field diameters (or IOR values), the OTDR sees different loss values depending on which end it's measuring from. Neither reading alone is accurate — the average is the true physical loss.
<div class="mth">True splice loss = (Loss_A_to_B + Loss_B_to_A) / 2

Example:
  A→B measures: +0.08 dB (normal)
  B→A measures: −0.04 dB (gainer artifact)
  True loss = (0.08 + (−0.04)) / 2 = 0.02 dB

The −0.04 dB "gain" is an artifact — in reality
the splice has 0.02 dB of true insertion loss.</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>A→B splice measurement (dB)</label><input type="number" id="bidir-ab" placeholder="e.g. 0.08" step="0.01" oninput="calcBidir()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>B→A splice measurement (dB)</label><input type="number" id="bidir-ba" placeholder="e.g. -0.04" step="0.01" oninput="calcBidir()"></div>
<div id="bidir-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Bidirectional -->
<div id="m11-bidir" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Break Location from Both Ends</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>When a fiber breaks, you can locate it from both ends and average for maximum accuracy. Averaging eliminates IOR errors if both measurements used the same IOR setting.</strong></div>
<div class="field"><label>Total fiber length (m)</label><input type="number" id="bk-total" placeholder="e.g. 10000" oninput="calcBreak()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Distance to break from End A (m)</label><input type="number" id="bk-a" placeholder="e.g. 6200" oninput="calcBreak()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Distance to break from End B (m)</label><input type="number" id="bk-b" placeholder="e.g. 3850" oninput="calcBreak()"></div>
<div id="bk-result" class="result"></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Bidirectional OTDR — When Required</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Situation</th><th>Bidirectional required?</th></tr>
<tr><td>Acceptance test — new installation</td><td class="pass">Yes — industry standard</td></tr>
<tr><td>Trouble locating (single break)</td><td class="warn">Recommended — improves accuracy</td></tr>
<tr><td>Splice loss measurement</td><td class="pass">Yes — for accurate splice loss</td></tr>
<tr><td>Quick fault location (emergency)</td><td class="warn">One end OK for quick locate</td></tr>
<tr><td>Routine periodic audit</td><td class="pass">Yes — compare to baseline</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Multi-Splice Bidirectional Log</h3>
