<div id="bidir-log-summary" style="margin-top:10px"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Ghost / Gainer -->
<div id="m11-ghost" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Ghost Reflection Identifier & Predictor</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A ghost is a false event that appears at exactly twice the distance of a strong reflector. After a strong Fresnel reflection (like a connector), some light bounces back to the OTDR, reflects again off the OTDR port, and makes a second trip down the fiber. It arrives looking like a real event at 2× the original distance.
<div class="mth">Ghost location prediction:
  d_ghost = 2 × d_real_reflector
  
  Ghost 2 (triple bounce):
  d_ghost2 = 3 × d_real_reflector
  
  Ghost amplitude ≈ Real_reflection − 2 × return_loss_dBm
  
  Identifying a ghost:
  1. Check if event distance is exactly 2× a known reflector
  2. Ghost has lower amplitude than the original
  3. Ghost disappears when original reflector is cleaned/fixed
  4. Ghost does NOT appear when testing from the other end</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Distance to suspected real reflector (m)</label><input type="number" id="gh-real" placeholder="e.g. 1500" oninput="calcGhost()"></div>
<div id="gh-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Gainer Splice Artifact — Theory & Calculator</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A "gainer" is when the OTDR shows a step UP at a splice — meaning the splice apparently added signal strength. This is physically impossible. It's caused by splicing two fibers with different mode field diameters (MFD). The backscatter coefficient changes at the splice — the fiber after the splice actually has stronger backscatter. The OTDR reads this as "more signal" even though there's actually loss.
<div class="mth">Gainer appears when:
  MFD_fiber2 > MFD_fiber1  (larger core after splice)
  Backscatter coefficient B ∝ 1/MFD²
  
  Apparent gain (A→B) ≈ B_change_dB − true_loss_dB
  
When B_change > true_loss:
  → Apparent gain (gainer artifact)
  
True loss is ALWAYS the bidirectional average:
  True_loss = (A→B + B→A) / 2
  Never report gainer as negative loss!</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>A→B measurement (shows gain, negative dB)</label><input type="number" id="gn-ab" placeholder="e.g. -0.05" step="0.01" oninput="calcGainer()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>B→A measurement (shows loss, positive dB)</label><input type="number" id="gn-ba" placeholder="e.g. 0.15" step="0.01" oninput="calcGainer()"></div>
<div id="gn-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Setup Guide -->
<div id="m11-setup" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>OTDR Setup — 6-Step Field Guide</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Clean everything:</strong> Clean the OTDR port, launch cable connectors, and all connectors on the cable under test with IEC 61300-3-35 compliant cleaning tools. Inspect with a fiber microscope before connecting. A dirty connector causes false events and inaccurate loss readings.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Set wavelength:</strong> Match the test wavelength to the operating wavelength. For SMF backhaul: test at both 1310 nm and 1550 nm. At 1310 nm you'll see splices and connectors more clearly. At 1550 nm you're more sensitive to bends. Test at the operating wavelength last.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Set IOR:</strong> Enter the IOR from the cable manufacturer's data sheet for your specific fiber. Common defaults: G.652 SMF at 1310nm = 1.4677. Wrong IOR = wrong distance readings.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Set range and pulse width:</strong> Range should be 1.5–2× the cable length. Pulse width: start with a short pulse (10–30 ns) for detail near the launch, then a longer pulse (100–275 ns) for the full span. For a 10 km cable, try 20 km range / 100 ns pulse first.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Set averaging time:</strong> For quick look: 15 seconds. For acceptance test: 3 minutes minimum. Longer averaging = lower noise floor = see farther. Dynamic range increases about 1 dB per 4× averaging time.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">6</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Connect launch cable, then test cable:</strong> OTDR port → launch cable → cable under test → tail cable (if available). Take the trace. Verify all expected events are visible and at the expected distances.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Wavelength Selection Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Wavelength</th><th>Best for</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>850 nm</td><td>Multimode fiber (OM1–OM4)</td><td>High attenuation, short distance only</td></tr>
<tr><td>1300 nm</td><td>Multimode (OM1–OM2) long-reach</td><td>Lower loss than 850 nm</td></tr>
<tr><td>1310 nm</td><td>SMF — splice/connector detail</td><td>Best for seeing individual events</td></tr>
<tr><td>1550 nm</td><td>SMF — bend sensitivity, long haul</td><td>More sensitive to macrobends than 1310</td></tr>
<tr><td>1625 nm</td><td>SMF — live fiber testing (out-of-band)</td><td>Used to test lit fiber without disruption</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">Always test at 1550 nm on SMF final acceptance — bends that are invisible at 1310 nm show up clearly at 1550. A splice organizer with a tight radius may show 0.0 dB at 1310 nm and 0.5 dB at 1550 nm. Always fix this before customer turn-up.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

