<div class="card">
<h3>OTDR Specifications Glossary</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
<tr><td>Dynamic range</td><td>Max measurable span loss (dB). Higher = tests longer spans.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Event dead zone (EDZ)</td><td>Min distance between two resolvable reflective events.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Attenuation dead zone (ADZ)</td><td>Distance after a reflection before accurate loss can be measured.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sampling resolution</td><td>Distance between data points on the trace (e.g., 0.1 m).</td></tr>
<tr><td>Spatial resolution</td><td>Min distance to separate two non-reflective events.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Linearity</td><td>Accuracy of loss measurement across the full dynamic range.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pulse width</td><td>Duration of the test pulse. Wider = more power = longer range but bigger dead zone.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Averaging time</td><td>How long the OTDR accumulates traces to reduce noise.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Return loss</td><td>How much light a reflector sends back. Higher = less reflection.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Backscatter level</td><td>Signal level of the continuous Rayleigh scatter (the trace slope).</td></tr>
<tr><td>IOR</td><td>Index of Refraction — ratio of light speed in vacuum to speed in fiber.</td></tr>
<tr><td>VoP</td><td>Velocity of Propagation = 1/IOR × c. Used for distance calculation.</td></tr>
