<!-- Fluke 289 -->
<div id="m12-f289" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Fluke 289 — True-RMS Logging Multimeter</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>The 289 is the workhorse CO DMM — True-RMS, data logging, and TrendCapture. Significantly better than a basic DMM for telecom work because it measures non-sinusoidal waveforms (like −48V with noise) accurately.</strong></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>DC voltage (−48V bus):</strong> Rotate to V̄ (DC). Red to bus, black to return. The 289 auto-ranges. For millivolt (shunt) measurements: use mV range or let auto-range settle.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>AC voltage (induction/hum):</strong> Rotate to V~ (AC). True-RMS measures distorted waveforms — critical for power influence measurements. Read 60 Hz hum on a telecom pair as AC millivolts.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>REL (relative) mode:</strong> Press REL to zero the display. Useful for measuring small voltage differences — e.g., voltage drop across a strap by zeroing at one end, then measuring at the other.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>TrendCapture / Logging:</strong> Press SHIFT + MIN MAX to start TrendCapture. Records readings over time and shows waveform graph. Invaluable for catching intermittent bus voltage dips during load changes.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Resistance:</strong> Rotate to Ω. Remove power from circuit first — resistance measured on a live circuit is meaningless and can damage the meter. Lead resistance: short the leads together, press REL to zero out lead resistance.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Fluke 289 CO Measurement Quick Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Measurement</th><th>Setting</th><th>Expected</th><th>Flag if</th></tr>
<tr><td>−48V bus voltage</td><td>V̄ DC</td><td>−52 to −54V</td><td>&lt;−48V or &gt;−56V</td></tr>
<tr><td>Shunt mV drop</td><td>mV DC (or auto)</td><td>0–50 mV typical</td><td>Erratic or &gt; rated mV</td></tr>
<tr><td>BOD strap drop</td><td>mV DC</td><td>&lt;5 mV</td><td>&gt;20 mV = corroded</td></tr>
<tr><td>Foreign AC on pair</td><td>mV AC (True-RMS)</td><td>&lt;500 mVrms</td><td>&gt;1 Vrms</td></tr>
<tr><td>Loop resistance</td><td>Ω (circuit de-energized)</td><td>Varies by gauge/length</td><td>Infinite = open; 0 = short</td></tr>
<tr><td>Continuity</td><td>))) (beep)</td><td>Beeps &lt;30Ω</td><td>No beep = open/high R</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">The 289's LoZ (low impedance) mode prevents phantom voltage readings on de-energized circuits. Press SHIFT + V to toggle LoZ. Essential when measuring on long cable runs that can accumulate static charge or capacitively coupled AC.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Fluke 87V -->
<div id="m12-f87" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Fluke 87V — Key Differences from 289</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>The 87V is the older sibling to the 289 — less data logging capability but just as accurate for field measurements. If you have an 87V, here's what's different.</strong></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Fluke 87V</th><th>Fluke 289</th></tr>
<tr><td>True-RMS</td><td class="pass">Yes</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data logging</td><td class="fail">No (MIN/MAX only)</td><td class="pass">Yes (TrendCapture)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Graphical display</td><td class="fail">No</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>PC interface</td><td class="fail">No</td><td class="pass">Yes (FlukeView)</td></tr>
<tr><td>LoZ mode</td><td class="fail">No</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Temperature input</td><td class="pass">Yes (K-type)</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Frequency measurement</td><td class="pass">Yes</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Duty cycle</td><td class="pass">Yes</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>87V POTS Line Test Sequence</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Foreign voltage check (line idle):</strong> V̄ DC — measure T-G, R-G, T-R. Should be near 0V all three. Then V~ AC — measure same three. Should be &lt;0.5 Vrms.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Battery feed check (on-hook):</strong> V̄ DC — measure T-G or T-R on an idle line. Should read −48V range. If reading 0V, check for cut pair or disconnected cross-connect.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Loop current (off-hook simulation):</strong> mA DC in series with a 390Ω resistor across the pair. Should read 18–50 mA for a working loop. &lt;18 mA = too long or high resistance.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Ring detection:</strong> V~ AC while ringing. Should read 50–90 Vrms at the CO; 40+ Vrms at the customer end.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>87V Reading Decoder</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Reading</th><th>Interpretation</th><th>Action</th></tr>
<tr><td>OL (overload)</td><td>Input exceeds range</td><td>Switch to higher range or check probe placement</td></tr>
<tr><td>−48 to −54V DC T-R</td><td>Normal battery feed</td><td>None</td></tr>
