<!-- Tempo 77HP -->
<div id="m12-tempo" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Tempo 77HP + 200EP Inductive Probe</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The 77HP is a tone generator. It puts an audible tone on a wire pair, which you then hunt with the 200EP inductive probe — no physical connection to the wire needed, just wave the probe near the cable until you hear the tone. Essential for pair identification and tracing.
</div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Basic pair identification:</strong> Clip 77HP red to tip, black to ring. Press tone button (guard 0, 1 Hz, or 4 Hz — use 4 Hz for clear identification). At the far end, use the 200EP to sweep near cable bundles — the toned pair gives the loudest signal.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Single conductor tracing:</strong> Clip only to one conductor. The tone will radiate from just that wire, allowing you to identify broken pairs where only one conductor is intact. Use "Radial" mode on the probe for this.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Probe technique:</strong> Hold probe parallel to the cable, not pointing at it. The 200EP is most sensitive along its length. Move slowly — a fast sweep misses short sections. The tone gets louder as you get closer to the correct pair.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>In a large cable bundle:</strong> Move the probe progressively closer to the cable until the loudest pair is identifiable. Touch pairs directly with the probe tip in metallic mode for closest discrimination in packed bundles.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Locating buried cable:</strong> Place 77HP on the pair at the CO. Walk the route with the 200EP pointed down toward the ground. You'll pick up the tone through several inches of soil — this traces the cable route and can locate buried splice cases.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Tone Generator Modes Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Mode</th><th>Use</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>Guard / Solid</td><td>Best discrimination in crowded bundles</td><td>Steady tone, minimal bleed to adjacent pairs</td></tr>
<tr><td>1 Hz flash</td><td>Standard pair ID in smaller bundles</td><td>Easy to distinguish aurally</td></tr>
<tr><td>4 Hz flash</td><td>Quick ID, good for training</td><td>Fast rate — unmistakable in field</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inductive (no clip)</td><td>Tracing through closed terminals</td><td>Less precise — use only when can't clip</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="wbox">Never apply a tone generator to a live circuit. Always verify the pair is de-energized first with a DMM. Applying 77HP tone to a line with −48V battery can damage the 77HP and potentially cause a CO alarm if you're connected to a live line card.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

