<h3>Anritsu MT9083 Access Master — OTDR</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>The MT9083 is a high-end field OTDR with OTDR, OPM (optical power meter), VFL (visual fault locator), and optional copper modules. Here's the field workflow.</strong></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Fiber Visualizer mode:</strong> Press FIBER VISUALIZER for a quick automated OTDR trace. The MT9083 auto-selects range and pulse width, takes a trace, and displays all detected events with loss values. Best for quick checks without manual setup.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Manual OTDR:</strong> Press OTDR → Manual. Set wavelength (1310/1550 nm), range (1.5–2× span length), pulse width (start at 100 ns for typical OSP spans), and averaging time (3 min for acceptance, 30 sec for quick look). Press START.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>OPM (Optical Power Meter):</strong> Press OPM. Connect the optical source to the far end. The MT9083 reads received optical power in dBm. Use this for end-to-end insertion loss testing — faster and simpler than OTDR for pass/fail checks on short links.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>VFL (Visual Fault Locator):</strong> Press VFL. The MT9083 injects visible red light (650 nm) into the fiber. Walk the route looking for red light glowing through the jacket — indicates a bend, crack, or break. Works up to ~5 km on good fiber.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Active fiber check:</strong> Before connecting OTDR to an unknown fiber, use the MT9083's OPM in receive mode to check for live optical power. Connecting an OTDR to a live fiber carrying data can damage the OTDR receiver and disrupt traffic.</span></div>
