<!-- T-BERD Workflow -->
<div id="m12-workflow" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>T-BERD Copper Workflow — ADSL Trouble</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>At the NID — basic loop check:</strong> Connect T-BERD copper module to the pair. Run Autotest. Check DC loop R, IR (T-G, R-G, T-R), AC voltage, and balance. Any fail here is a physical plant issue — document it before troubleshooting further.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>If loop checks pass — noise test:</strong> Run noise floor measurement. ADSL needs &lt;−40 dBrn noise floor for reliable service. If noise is elevated, run impulse noise test for 1 minute. &gt;4 impulses/minute above threshold indicates a noise source problem.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>TDR check for bridge taps:</strong> Run TDR. Look for bumps (bridge taps) along the trace. Any tap &gt;200 ft on an ADSL loop significantly degrades performance. Document location, flag for removal.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>DSL line simulation:</strong> Connect as golden modem to the DSLAM port. Record actual sync rate, SNR margin, and attenuation. If these are worse than expected for the loop length, the problem is noise or DSLAM configuration — not the physical loop.</span></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>T-BERD T1 Turn-Up Workflow</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Verify framing:</strong> Get the framing type (ESF or D4) from the order. Set T-BERD to match. Wrong framing = immediate LOF.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Connect and verify signal:</strong> Bantam jacks at DSX. Check for LOS first — no signal = physical problem before any other testing.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Run BERT with loopback:</strong> Request loopback at CPE (CSU loopback). Run BERT for minimum 15 minutes. Zero errors = clean span. Any errors = investigate span before customer turn-up.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Release loopback and verify live:</strong> Release loopback, verify circuit passes traffic end-to-end. Confirm with customer or NOC before clearing the work order.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>ESF vs D4 Framing — Quick Reference</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>D4 (SF)</th><th>ESF</th></tr>
<tr><td>Superframe length</td><td>12 frames</td><td>24 frames</td></tr>
<tr><td>CRC-6 error monitoring</td><td class="fail">No</td><td class="pass">Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data link channel</td><td class="fail">No</td><td class="pass">Yes (4 kbps FDL)</td></tr>
<tr><td>In-service monitoring</td><td class="fail">Limited</td><td class="pass">Full ESF statistics</td></tr>
<tr><td>Error accumulation</td><td>BPV only</td><td>BPV + CRC + ES/SES/UAS</td></tr>
<tr><td>Still in use?</td><td class="warn">Legacy — being retired</td><td class="pass">Current standard</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">If you see a circuit with D4 framing, flag it for upgrade to ESF. D4 has no performance monitoring capability — you can't tell if a circuit is degrading until it fails completely. ESF gives you advance warning through CRC error accumulation.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- General Tips -->
<div id="m12-tips" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>6 Rules Every Field Tech Should Know</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Test before you touch.</strong> Always take a baseline measurement before making any change. You need to know the before-state to prove your work made things better — and to know what you're dealing with.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Clean before you connect.</strong> Dirty fiber connectors are the #1 cause of elevated insertion loss. Dirty DMM probes cause wrong voltage readings. Clean every connection before measuring or connecting signal.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Disconnect power before measuring resistance.</strong> Resistance measured on a live circuit is meaningless — the DMM reads a combination of the circuit voltage and the resistance, producing a garbage result. Always de-energize first.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Document everything.</strong> Write down every measurement with the date, location, meter used, and tech name. If you don't write it down, it didn't happen. Measurements without documentation are useless for trending and liability.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Calibrate your tool before relying on it.</strong> Check your DMM against a known voltage source. Zero your OTDR dead zones with a launch cable. Verify your tone generator is actually producing tone. Equipment fails — verify before trusting.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">6</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Understand the measurement, not just the number.</strong> A reading of 450Ω loop resistance means nothing unless you know whether it's within spec for the service type and cable gauge. Context makes measurements meaningful.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Tool Selection Guide</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Task</th><th>Best tool</th><th>Fallback</th></tr>
<tr><td>DC voltage / shunt mV</td><td>Fluke 289 or 87V</td><td>Any True-RMS DMM</td></tr>
<tr><td>DSL loop qualification</td><td>Fluke Sidekick VIP</td><td>Fluke 990DSL</td></tr>
<tr><td>DSL modem simulation</td><td>Fluke 990DSL (golden modem)</td><td>T-BERD copper module</td></tr>
<tr><td>T1 / DS1 testing</td><td>VIAVI T-BERD or JDSU MCT-8000</td><td>Any DS1 BERT tester</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pair identification / tracing</td><td>Tempo 77HP + 200EP</td><td>Any tone + probe set</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fiber OTDR</td><td>Anritsu MT9083 or VIAVI T-BERD</td><td>Any calibrated OTDR</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fiber power measurement</td><td>OPM (any brand, calibrated)</td><td>OTDR in OPM mode</td></tr>
<tr><td>BOD / strap mV drop</td><td>Fluke 289 in mV mode</td><td>Any sensitive mV DMM</td></tr>
<tr><td>Impulse noise</td><td>Fluke Sidekick VIP</td><td>T-BERD copper module</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ethernet RFC 2544</td><td>VIAVI T-BERD</td><td>Ixia or Spirent tester</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="wbox">Battery and maintenance: charge OTDRs and test sets after every use. A dead battery on site costs more in lost time than the cost of a charging station. Keep spare batteries for every major tool. Clean optical adapters with every use — one dirty connector can contaminate the OTDR port and require depot service.</div>
