<!-- Voltage Measurement -->
<div id="m13-voltage" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>How a DMM Measures Voltage</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A voltmeter is basically a very high-value resistor with a current meter in series. Because the internal resistance is extremely high (10 MΩ typical), almost no current flows through the meter — so it doesn't disturb the circuit being measured. The voltage is calculated from V = I × R_internal.
<div class="mth">Voltmeter input impedance: ~10 MΩ (standard DMM)
  Loading error = V × (R_load / (R_load + R_meter))
  
  At 10 MΩ input impedance:
  If circuit source impedance = 1 MΩ:
  Error = 1/(1+10) × 100% = 9% low → significant!
  
  If circuit source impedance = 1 kΩ:
  Error = 0.001/10 × 100% = 0.01% → negligible

For telecom: 99% of measurements are low-impedance
  (battery bus, cable pairs, shunts) → no loading error.</div></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>When Phantom Voltage Appears</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Phantom voltage is a false reading on a de-energized wire caused by capacitive coupling from an adjacent energized conductor.</strong>
<div class="mth">Long cable runs act as capacitors — adjacent live wires
capacitively couple voltage into de-energized conductors.
Your high-impedance meter reads this voltage as "real."

Fix: Use LoZ (Low Impedance) mode on your meter.
  LoZ input impedance: ~3.5 kΩ instead of 10 MΩ
  Loads down the capacitive coupling to near zero.
  If the voltage reading drops dramatically in LoZ mode:
  → Phantom voltage — circuit is actually de-energized.
  If reading stays the same in LoZ:
  → Real voltage — there IS an energized source.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>AC vs DC Voltage Measurement</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>AC measurement theory:</strong> AC voltage is not a single value — it's constantly changing. DMMs use one of two methods to report a single number:<br><br>
<strong>Average-responding with RMS calibration:</strong> Measures the average of the rectified waveform, then multiplies by 1.1107 (the ratio of RMS to average for a pure sine wave). Works accurately on sine waves only. Reads wrong on distorted waveforms.<br><br>
<strong>True-RMS:</strong> Computes the actual RMS (Root Mean Square) value regardless of waveform shape. Required for accurate measurements on non-sinusoidal waveforms like square waves, switching power supply noise, and distorted AC in power rooms.
<div class="mth">RMS definition: V_rms = √(mean(v²))
  For pure sine: V_rms = V_peak / √2 = 0.7071 × V_peak
  
  Average-responding on square wave (crest factor = 1):
  Reads: 0.707 × V_peak (sine assumption)
  Actual: 1.000 × V_peak (square wave)
  → Error: 41% LOW! 

True-RMS on square wave: reads correctly.</div></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Resistance -->
<div id="m13-resistance" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>How a DMM Measures Resistance</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A DMM forces a known constant current through the unknown resistance, then measures the voltage that develops. R = V/I. The meter's internal battery powers this constant current source — which is why you must de-energize the circuit before measuring resistance. If there's an external voltage source, it adds to the meter's voltage reading and gives a wrong result.
<div class="mth">Ω measurement principle:
  I_known = constant current (typically 0.1–1 mA)
  V_measured = I_known × R_unknown
  R_displayed = V_measured / I_known

Why external voltage ruins the reading:
  V_total = V_meter + V_external
  R_displayed = (V_meter + V_external) / I_known
  
  Example: 5V on a pair, meter expects 0V:
  R_displayed = (1mV + 5000mV) / 0.001A = 5,001 Ω
  (completely wrong)</div></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Capacitance Effect on Resistance Measurement</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Long cables have capacitance. This capacitance charges up during resistance measurement, causing the reading to drift before settling.</strong>
<div class="mth">Cable capacitance: ~15.7 nF/mile for 24 AWG PIC
A 3-mile loop has: 3 × 15.7 = 47 nF total capacitance

During resistance measurement:
  Meter charges the capacitance with its constant current
  Reading drifts from high → settles to true value
  
Wait time to settle: t ≈ 5 × R × C
  At 500Ω loop, 47 nF: t ≈ 5 × 500 × 47e-9 = 0.12 ms
  (very fast — negligible for most tests)
  
  At 50,000Ω loop, 47 nF: t ≈ 5 × 50e3 × 47e-9 = 11.75 ms
  (still fast — but on high-R circuits, allow meter to settle)</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Resistance Measurement Best Practices</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">1</span><span class="stxt"><strong>De-energize the circuit.</strong> Any voltage in the circuit will make the resistance reading wrong. Turn off power, disconnect batteries, discharge capacitors.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">2</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Zero your leads (REL/NULL).</strong> Your test leads have resistance (0.1–0.5Ω typically). For measurements below 10Ω, this error matters. Short the leads together, press REL or NULL to zero it out.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">3</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Don't touch the probes.</strong> Your body resistance (typically 10kΩ–1MΩ wet to dry) adds a parallel path across the measurement. Keep fingers on probe insulation only.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">4</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Wait for reading to settle.</strong> On high-resistance circuits with cable capacitance, the reading may drift before settling. Wait 3–5 seconds after connecting probes before recording.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">5</span><span class="stxt"><strong>For very low resistance (&lt;10Ω):</strong> Use a 4-wire (Kelvin) measurement. Standard 2-wire measurement includes lead resistance — at 0.3Ω total leads + 0.5Ω target, you're reading 0.8Ω (60% error).</span></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Current -->
<div id="m13-current" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>How a DMM Measures Current</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> An ammeter works by inserting a very small resistance (shunt) into the circuit path. The voltage drop across this shunt, divided by the shunt's resistance, gives the current. The shunt must be small enough that inserting it doesn't significantly change the circuit current — this is why ammeters should have near-zero resistance.
<div class="mth">Ammeter shunt principle:
  I = V_shunt / R_shunt
  
  DMM shunt resistances:
  A range (10A): ~0.01 Ω → at 10A: 0.1V drop
  mA range (400mA): ~1.0 Ω → at 400mA: 0.4V drop
  µA range: ~10 Ω
  
  Insertion error (voltage consumed by meter):
  V_error = I × R_shunt
  This voltage is "stolen" from the circuit — usually negligible
  for high-voltage circuits, but significant for low-voltage loops.</div></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Why Different Jacks for Different Current Ranges</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> The high-current jack (10A on most DMMs) has a different internal shunt — very low resistance for high current. The mA/µA jack has a higher resistance shunt. If you plug into the 10A jack and measure on the mA range, the reading will be wrong. Worse — if you plug into the mA jack with 10A flowing, you'll blow the internal fuse. Always check which jack your leads are in before measuring current.
</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Current Measurement Safety</h3>
<div class="dbox">The most dangerous DMM mistake: leaving probes in the current (A or mA) jacks and then measuring voltage. In current mode, the DMM has near-zero input impedance — connecting it across a voltage source creates a direct short. This can destroy the meter, blow the fuse, arc, or cause personal injury. Always move probes to voltage jacks before measuring voltage.</div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>DC Loop Current for POTS Qualification</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Measuring loop current confirms the complete circuit is working and the loop resistance is within spec for POTS service.</strong>
<div class="mth">Test setup:
  Connect mA meter in series with a 390Ω load resistor
  across the pair at the NID (simulates off-hook phone)
  
  I_loop = V_battery / (R_loop + R_load + R_source)
  
  Typical values:
  V_battery = 48V, R_loop = 500Ω, R_load = 390Ω, R_src = 200Ω
  I = 48 / (500 + 390 + 200) = 48 / 1090 = 44 mA ✓
  
  Min for DTMF: 18 mA
  Max (fuse trip risk): 120 mA on most line cards</div></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- True-RMS -->
<div id="m13-truerms" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>True-RMS — What It Is and Why It Matters</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> RMS (Root Mean Square) is the DC equivalent of an AC waveform — the DC voltage that would produce the same heating effect in a resistor. For a pure sine wave, RMS = peak ÷ √2. But for any other shape, you have to compute it properly.
<div class="mth">True-RMS formula:
  V_rms = √( (1/T) × ∫v²(t)dt )
  
  For pure sine: V_rms = 0.7071 × V_peak  (crest factor = 1.414)
  For square wave: V_rms = V_peak          (crest factor = 1.0)
  For triangular: V_rms = 0.5774 × V_peak (crest factor = 1.732)
  
  Crest factor = V_peak / V_rms
  Higher crest factor = more "peaky" waveform

  Average-responding meters assume crest factor = 1.414
  They multiply the average by 1.1107 and call it RMS.
  On non-sinusoidal waveforms: wrong!</div></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>True-RMS Error Table</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Waveform</th><th>Crest factor</th><th>Avg-responding reads</th><th>True-RMS reads</th><th>Error</th></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td>Pure sine</td><td>1.414</td><td>Correct</td><td>Correct</td><td>0%</td></tr>
<tr><td>Square wave (50% duty)</td><td>1.000</td><td>11% low</td><td>Correct</td><td>11%</td></tr>
<tr><td>Triangle wave</td><td>1.732</td><td>4% high</td><td>Correct</td><td>4%</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pulse (10% duty cycle)</td><td>3.162</td><td>65% low</td><td>Correct</td><td>65%</td></tr>
<tr><td>Power line with harmonics</td><td>1.5–2.0</td><td>Wrong by 5–30%</td><td>Correct</td><td>Varies</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Three Ways DMMs Compute True-RMS</h3>
<div class="eli5">
<strong>1. Analog (thermal) method:</strong> Heats a resistor with the actual signal, compares to a DC-heated reference until they match. Accurate to high crest factors but slow and temperature-sensitive. Used in lab-grade meters.<br><br>
<strong>2. Digital sampling + computation:</strong> Samples the waveform many times per cycle, squares each sample, averages the squares, takes the square root. Fast and accurate. Used in Fluke 87V, 289, and most modern True-RMS DMMs. Limited by sampling rate — can't capture very high-frequency content.<br><br>
<strong>3. Hybrid (AD637 or similar IC):</strong> Uses an analog squaring circuit followed by digital processing. Most common in mid-grade True-RMS meters. Works well for crest factors up to 3–5.
</div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>When True-RMS Matters in the CO</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Use True-RMS for:</strong><br>
• Power influence measurements on cable pairs (power line harmonics are highly non-sinusoidal)<br>
• Longitudinal balance testing (noise has complex waveform)<br>
• Measuring AC ripple on −48V DC bus (switching noise has high crest factor)<br>
• Any noise measurement where waveform shape is unknown<br><br>
<strong>Average-responding is fine for:</strong><br>
• Measuring utility line voltage (close to pure sine)<br>
• Generator output voltage (close to sine)<br>
• Ringer voltage at CO (sine wave from SLIC)</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Clamp Meter -->
<div id="m13-clamp" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Clamp Meter — AC (Transformer Action)</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> An AC clamp meter is a current transformer. The wire being measured is the primary (one turn). The clamp jaw is the transformer core. The secondary winding inside the clamp produces a tiny current proportional to the primary current. No physical contact with the conductor is needed.
<div class="mth">Transformer current ratio:
  I_secondary = I_primary / N_secondary_turns
  
  At N = 1000 turns and I_primary = 100A:
  I_secondary = 100 / 1000 = 0.1A (100 mA)
  
  Why AC only:
  Transformer action requires changing flux (dΦ/dt)
  DC produces constant flux — no changing flux
  → No induced secondary current → No DC reading
  
  The clamp reads zero on DC regardless of current!</div></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Hall Effect DC Clamp Meter</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A Hall effect sensor in the clamp jaw detects the magnetic field produced by DC current. The magnetic field is proportional to current regardless of whether it's AC or DC.
<div class="mth">Hall effect principle:
  Magnetic field B ∝ I (current in conductor)
  Hall voltage V_H ∝ B × I_bias / thickness
  
  The Hall sensor has a small bias current.
  The conductor's magnetic field deflects this current,
  producing a Hall voltage proportional to measured current.
  
  DC clamp meter problem: residual magnetism
  If you've measured a large current, the steel jaw retains
  some residual magnetism that offsets the zero reading.
  Fix: press ZERO/NULL before each measurement.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Clamp Meter in the CO — −48V Plant</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>AC clamp meters cannot measure −48V DC current.</strong> You need either a DC Hall effect clamp or the shunt mV method.<br><br>
<strong>What a DC clamp meter needs:</strong><br>
• Hall effect sensor (not transformer type)<br>
• Zero adjustment (to cancel residual magnetism)<br>
• Adequate jaw size for the bus bar or cable<br><br>
<strong>Practical field tip:</strong> Most CO techs don't carry a DC clamp meter. Use the shunt mV method instead — it's built into every plant with a shunt installed, and any DMM reads it.
</div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<div class="eli5"><strong>Worked example — DC clamp on a −48V bus:</strong>
<div class="mth">Plant shunt: 50mV / 400A
Measured mV: 24.5 mV

I = (24.5 / 50) × 400 = 196 A

This is the same result you'd get with a $1,500 DC
clamp meter, using only a $200 DMM in mV mode.
The shunt IS the current sensor — use it.</div></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Capacitance -->
<div id="m13-cap" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Capacitance Measurement — Constant Current Method</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> A DMM measures capacitance by forcing a known constant current into the capacitor and timing how fast the voltage rises. A larger capacitor takes longer to charge — so the charge time is proportional to capacitance.
<div class="mth">Charging equation: v(t) = (I / C) × t
  C = I × t / v
  
  DMM method:
  1. Applies known constant current I
  2. Waits until voltage reaches reference level V_ref
  3. Measures time t
  4. Computes C = I × t / V_ref
  
  Cable capacitance application:
  C_cable = L × C_per_unit
  L (feet) = C_measured (nF) / C_per_unit (nF/ft)
  
  24 AWG PIC: 83 nF/km = 0.0253 nF/ft
  At 10,000 ft: C = 10,000 × 0.0253 = 253 nF</div></div>
<div class="field"><label>Measured capacitance (nF)</label><input type="number" id="cm-c" placeholder="e.g. 253" step="0.1" oninput="calcCM()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Cable type</label>
<select id="cm-type" onchange="calcCM()">
<option value="0.0253">24 AWG PIC — 0.0253 nF/ft</option>
<option value="0.0253">22 AWG PIC — 0.0253 nF/ft</option>
<option value="0.0268">19 AWG PIC — 0.0268 nF/ft</option>
<option value="custom">Custom nF/ft</option>
</select></div>
<div id="cm-custom-f" style="display:none">
<div class="field"><label>Custom nF/ft</label><input type="number" id="cm-cu" step="0.0001" oninput="calcCM()"></div>
</div>
<div id="cm-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Capacitance FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My meter reads capacitance on a pair that's in service. Is that a problem?</div>
<div class="faq-a">No — all copper pairs have capacitance. The measured value just tells you the conductor length. What matters is whether it matches what you expect for the cable length and gauge.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: I measured capacitance on an open pair and got an infinite reading. Normal?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Yes, if the far end is truly open (not connected to anything). The capacitance test only works if the pair has a defined length with a reasonable capacitance — very short stubs or completely open pairs may read zero or OL.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My capacitance reading on a break fault keeps changing each time I measure.</div>
<div class="faq-a">This usually indicates a wet or intermittent fault. When moisture is present at the break, the capacitance varies with water movement or temperature. Consistent readings require a clean, stable fault.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Why does my DMM beep or act erratically when measuring cable capacitance?</div>
<div class="faq-a">The cable pair is acting as a charged capacitor — it may have residual voltage from a previous measurement or battery feed. Discharge the pair (short tip and ring to ground for 5 seconds) before measuring capacitance.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- 4-Wire Kelvin -->
<div id="m13-kelvin" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>4-Wire (Kelvin) Resistance Measurement</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> In a standard 2-wire measurement, your test leads are in series with the resistance you're measuring. If your leads have 0.2Ω total resistance and you're measuring a 0.5Ω target, you read 0.7Ω — a 40% error. 4-wire measurement solves this by using separate pairs of leads for current and voltage.
<div class="mth">2-wire measurement:
  R_displayed = R_target + R_lead1 + R_lead2
  
  4-wire (Kelvin) measurement:
  Force current through outer leads (C+, C−)
  Measure voltage with inner leads (V+, V−)
  Lead resistance drops out because:
  V_measured = I × R_target only
  (no current flows through voltage leads → no V drop)
  
  R_true = V_measured / I_force
  
Required when:
  Target R &lt; 10× lead resistance
  i.e., if leads = 0.3Ω, use 4-wire for R &lt; 3Ω</div></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>4-Wire Applications in Telecom</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Measurement</th><th>Typical value</th><th>Why 4-wire?</th></tr>
<tr><td>Battery return bus to MGB</td><td>5–10 mΩ</td><td>Lead R (300mΩ) >> target</td></tr>
<tr><td>BDFB frame bond</td><td>10–100 mΩ</td><td>Lead R comparable to target</td></tr>
<tr><td>Bus strap resistance</td><td>0.1–2 mΩ</td><td>Absolutely requires 4-wire</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fuse holder contact R</td><td>0.5–5 mΩ</td><td>Must use 4-wire to see difference</td></tr>
<tr><td>Loop R on 24 AWG at 100ft</td><td>~5.1 Ω</td><td>2-wire OK — target >> lead R</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cable shield continuity</td><td>0.15–1.5 Ω</td><td>Usually 2-wire OK; 4-wire for short runs</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="tip">The Fluke 289 and most quality DMMs have a 4-wire Ω mode. Check your meter's manual. Some meters require a special lead set for 4-wire mode. For CO grounding measurements, a dedicated milliohm meter (like the Fluke 1550C or Megger) is the professional tool.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Meter FAQs -->
<div id="m13-meterfaq" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Meter FAQs — General</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My meter reads voltage on a pair that the OSS says is de-energized. Is it real?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Possibly phantom voltage from capacitive coupling. Switch to LoZ mode — if the reading drops dramatically (or to zero), it was phantom. If it stays, there's a real voltage source: could be battery from an active line card, foreign power, or a live line cross-connected to this pair.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My resistance reading is drifting — it started high and is slowly coming down.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Normal behavior on long cable runs. The cable capacitance is being charged by the meter's constant current source. Wait for the reading to stabilize (usually 5–30 seconds). If it never stabilizes, suspect a leaky capacitor or moisture in the cable.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: I measured resistance with reversed polarity (red and black swapped). Does it matter?</div>
<div class="faq-a">For pure resistance, no — Ohm's law is symmetric. For semiconductors (diodes, transistors), yes — polarity determines whether the junction is forward or reverse biased. For cable pairs, polarity doesn't matter.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Should I use manual or auto range?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Auto range is fine for most measurements. Use manual range when: (1) you know the approximate value and want faster settling; (2) the signal is fluctuating near a range boundary (auto range can hunt between ranges); (3) you're logging data and need a consistent display format.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My meter accuracy spec says ±0.5% + 2 digits. What does the "+ 2 digits" mean?</div>
<div class="faq-a">It's the least-significant digit (LSD) error. On a 4-digit display reading 100.0V, ±2 digits means ±0.2V. The total error at 100V is ±(0.5V + 0.2V) = ±0.7V. At lower readings, the digit error becomes relatively more important.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: What's the difference between accuracy and resolution?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Resolution is the smallest change the display can show (e.g., 0.1 mV on the 600mV range). Accuracy is how close the displayed value is to the true value. A meter can have excellent resolution but poor accuracy. For telecom work, you generally need both — the mV shunt readings require both high resolution and accuracy.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Accuracy & Calibration FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: How often should I calibrate my DMM?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Most calibration standards (NIST traceability, ISO 17025) recommend annual calibration. For CO work, follow your company's instrument calibration program. A meter that hasn't been calibrated in 3+ years should be verified against a known reference before trusting for critical measurements.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Can I calibrate my own meter in the field?</div>
<div class="faq-a">You can verify it using a calibration source or reference meter — not true calibration. True calibration adjusts internal constants and is done by a certified lab with NIST-traceable standards. Field verification against another calibrated meter can catch gross errors but won't reveal small but significant drift.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My meter failed a calibration check. How much error is acceptable?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Depends on the measurement. For a DC voltage check at 50V, ±0.5% = ±0.25V. For mV shunt readings where 1mV = 4A, even 0.5% error matters. Use the manufacturer's spec as the acceptance limit — if the meter fails its published accuracy spec, it needs calibration or repair.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Copper FAQs -->
<div id="m13-copperfaq" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Copper Plant FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Customer's DSL won't train on a 12,000 ft 24 AWG pair that passes all loop tests.</div>
<div class="faq-a">First, verify there are no load coils (check LFACS/ACIS records). Even one coil completely blocks DSL. Second, check for bridge taps — even 200 ft taps cause reflections that prevent DSL sync. Third, check the DSLAM port isn't in a bad line card slot. A loop that physically qualifies but won't train is often a load coil (check records) or bad DSLAM port.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Trouble disappears during dry weather and comes back when it rains.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Classic symptom of a wet splice or damaged cable sheath. Moisture lowers insulation resistance, which drops during rain and recovers when dry. Check IR on the pair during rain — it will be much lower than normal. Locate the nearest splice cases on the route and check for water infiltration.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: I'm measuring DC voltage T-G and R-G on an idle line. T-G shows −48V but R-G shows 0V.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Open ring conductor. The ring wire is broken somewhere between your test point and the CO. The tip is intact (shows battery), but ring has no return path. Run a Murray loop or TDR from the ring conductor to locate the break.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: T1 circuit shows BPV errors that come and go. Everything tests clean when I'm on-site.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Classic bridge tap problem or a wet section near the loop threshold. Bridge taps cause reflections that produce BPV errors in AMI T1 coding, especially near the LBO threshold. The errors may only appear at certain temperatures (cold = higher resistance = more loss = closer to threshold). Leave a T-BERD in alarm monitor mode for 24 hours to capture the pattern.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>More Copper FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My TDR shows what looks like a fault at 3,000 ft on a 24 AWG cable. Could it be a load coil?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Almost certainly yes. H88 load coils are placed at 3,000 ft from the CO. A load coil appears as a high-impedance event on a TDR — a positive reflection (open-like). If it appears at exactly 3,000 ft, 9,000 ft, 15,000 ft, etc., you've found the load coil locations. This also confirms DSL won't work without removing them.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: I have a ground fault that shows on T-G and R-G equally. What does that mean?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Equal faults on both conductors usually means a cable section has flooded — both conductors share the same water in the cable sheath. Or it could be a sheath ground where both conductors contact the shield. Unlike a metallic T-R fault, this one will affect both conductors simultaneously and often affects all pairs in the same section.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Continuity tester beeps between T and R (shows continuity) but my DMM reads 1,500Ω.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Classic gotcha — see the Gotchas tab. The continuity tester beeps for anything below ~2kΩ, which can be a legitimate high-resistance fault, a bridge tap with load, or even a legitimate line card still connected. Always measure with a DMM for the actual resistance value.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Fiber FAQs -->
<div id="m13-fiberfaq" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Fiber Optic FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: OTDR shows increased splice loss on a splice I did last month. It was 0.02 dB then, now it's 0.15 dB. What happened?</div>
<div class="faq-a">The most common cause is a mechanical stress change at the splice — either the splice organizer was overfilled and is now bending fibers, or water got into the splice closure and froze/swelled, stressing the fiber at the splice point. Re-test bidirectionally to confirm the loss increase is real. If confirmed, open the closure and inspect.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: I'm testing a fiber with VFL and can see red light coming through the jacket for about 6 feet, but no obvious break.</div>
<div class="faq-a">This is a tight bend radius violation. The fiber is bent too sharply over that section — light escapes through the cladding/jacket. Find and relieve the bend (typically a cable routing issue, a too-tight tie wrap, or a cable stapled at 90°). The loss may be 1–10 dB depending on how tight the bend is.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: My OTDR shows a gainer (negative loss) at a splice. Does that mean the splice is perfect?</div>
<div class="faq-a">No — it's an artifact, not a measurement. See the Gainer Splice section in Module 11. You must measure bidirectionally and average both results to get the true splice loss. A gainer reading from one direction is meaningless on its own.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Two OTDRs tested the same span and show different lengths by 50 meters. Which is right?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Likely an IOR mismatch between the two instruments. Check what IOR each was set to. If one was set to 1.4677 and the other to 1.4682, the 50m difference on a 10km span is exactly what you'd expect. Get the correct IOR from the cable reel documentation and re-test with both instruments set identically.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>More Fiber FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Customer reports their fiber service goes down intermittently for 1–2 minutes, then comes back.</div>
<div class="faq-a">This pattern — brief outage then self-recovery — is classic for a connector with intermittent contact or a fiber with a stress-related break that's near the threshold. Test the link end-to-end with an OPM while flexing each connector. If you can reproduce the outage by moving a specific connector, that's your problem. Also check for thermal expansion effects: does it happen at a specific time of day (temperature change)?</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: I tested a span and the OTDR shows 0.5 dB higher loss than when it was installed. No obvious events on the trace.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Gradual loss increase without a localized event usually means distributed microbending — the cable jacket is under stress along a section. Check for areas where cable was buried with sharp rocks or where conduit may have shifted. Also check for any locations where the cable route has had excavation work nearby.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- CO Power FAQs -->
<div id="m13-cofaq" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>CO Power Room FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Bus voltage drops 2–3 volts during busy-hour traffic peaks. Is this normal?</div>
<div class="faq-a">No — it indicates excessive resistance in the distribution path. Measure mV drops across each major connection point (straps, lugs, breakers, bus sections) under load. A 2V drop at 300A implies 6.7 mΩ of resistance, which is too high. Look for corroded connections, undersized straps, or loose lug connections.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Generator starts but bus voltage still drops to low alarm when load transfers. Batteries are charged.</div>
<div class="faq-a">This is almost always battery internal resistance, not a capacity problem. Aged VRLA batteries can have very high internal resistance even at 100% state of charge — they simply can't deliver current without a large voltage sag. Test with a battery capacity tester (load bank) to confirm. If the battery holds charge but sags under load, the batteries need replacement regardless of their SOC.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: BDFB shunt reads zero but the equipment downstream is powered. How?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Three possibilities: (1) Shunt is wired backwards — measuring the wrong direction; (2) Shunt wiring to the controller is open — the shunt has current but the controller sees no signal; (3) Parallel feed — current is being delivered by a different path that bypasses the shunt (check for any non-fused connections). Measure mV directly across the shunt with a DMM to verify.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Battery string shows −49V on float — lower than expected −52 to −54V.</div>
<div class="faq-a">This could mean: (1) One or more cells have failed internally and are being bypassed; (2) The float voltage setpoint is misconfigured on the rectifier; (3) The battery is discharging (AC power interruption you're not aware of). Measure individual cell voltages. A failed cell reads close to 0V or significantly lower than others. Check rectifier output at the rectifier terminals.</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>More CO Power FAQs</h3>
<div class="faq-q">Q: We replaced all the VRLA batteries 3 years ago but are already seeing voltage sag issues.</div>
<div class="faq-a">Three years is early for quality VRLA — check the battery room temperature. If the room runs at 90°F (32°C) instead of 77°F (25°C), battery life is cut nearly in half. Also check that the rectifier float voltage is set correctly — overcharging (above 2.25V/cell) dramatically shortens VRLA life. Get the batteries capacity-tested to confirm actual capacity vs. rated.</div>
<div class="faq-q">Q: Plant controller shows different current than my mV shunt calculation. Which is right?</div>
<div class="faq-a">Your direct mV measurement is more reliable. Plant controllers drift over time and may be calibrated to a shunt that has since been replaced or has a slightly different resistance. If the discrepancy is greater than 5%, recalibrate the controller using your measured mV and the known shunt rating. Document both readings and the calibration action.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- Classic Gotchas -->
<div id="m13-gotchas" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Classic Gotchas — Things That Trip Up Everyone</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>These are the measurement traps that catch experienced techs. Know them before you find them the hard way.</strong></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Resistance open but current flows normally.</strong> You test loop resistance, get infinite (OL). But the customer has dial tone and the loop current is 38 mA. How? The pair you're testing at the NID is NOT the same pair as the active circuit. Tone test to verify which pair is actually connected to the active line card before running any tests.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Wrong pair toned.</strong> You tone out pair 5 and get a response. You go to the terminal. The toned pair is actually pair 8 — someone has labeled the terminal wrong, or you miscounted from the wrong end of the binder. Always verify pair color code (T-G, R-G) before splicing or cross-connecting.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Continuity beeps but resistance reads 1,500Ω.</strong> The continuity function on most meters beeps for anything below 2,000Ω. A 1,500Ω reading is NOT a good pair — it's a fault that just happens to be within the beep threshold. Always use the Ω function to get the actual value. A good pair should read near-zero (a few ohms) on a short loop or the expected loop resistance for its length.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Fiber gainer reported as "no loss."</strong> Tech measures a splice from one direction, sees a negative value (−0.04 dB), and writes "0 dB loss" in the report. The true loss is the bidirectional average — may be 0.05 dB or higher. Always measure bidirectionally and record the average.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>BDFB discrepancy.</strong> Sum of branch currents is 20A less than the main shunt. Tech assumes shunt drift. Actually: a BDFB breaker was removed and the slot was covered, but the circuit is still energized through a direct connection that bypasses the breaker position. Check for any feeds that don't run through a metered breaker.</span></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>More Classic Gotchas</h3>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>OTDR says fiber is 15,847 ft. Records say 15,000 ft. Wrong IOR?</strong> Maybe — but first check if there's a service loop at each end. Standard practice is to leave 100–200 ft of coiled cable at each splice case and termination point. That extra 847 ft = about 4 splice cases with standard service loops. Map the splice points before assuming IOR error.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>Loop current is fine but customer can't hear dialtone.</strong> The physical loop is working. But the customer's phone works like this: loop current flows → SLIC detects off-hook → routes audio from CO switch. If there's no audio but loop current is normal, the problem is in the switch programming or the customer's phone/wiring — not the cable pair. Verify at the NID with a butt set (handset).</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>DSL trains but immediately retrains.</strong> Loop parameters look perfect. Modem connects then drops every few minutes. Classic symptom of impulse noise — too brief to affect loop qualification tests but frequent enough to cause DSL retrains. Run a 24-hour impulse noise test. Also check for loose connections at the NID that create noise when the wind moves the cable.</span></div>
<div class="step"><span class="sn">!</span><span class="stxt"><strong>T1 BPV count goes up only at night.</strong> Span was clean all day. Errors accumulate between midnight and 6am. This is almost certainly a thermal expansion issue — the cable cools overnight, conductor resistance increases, and the marginal span (already near the 22.5 dB limit) goes over threshold. The fix is adding a span extender or rerouting to a shorter path — not a physical damage issue.</span></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

