<div id="m14-thermo" class="stab-page">
<div class="grid">
<div class="card">
<h3>Thermography — ΔT Meaning</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> An infrared camera shows temperature differences, not absolute temperatures. The key measurement is ΔT — the temperature difference between a hot component and a reference (either ambient air or a similar nearby component under the same load). A bigger ΔT means a more serious problem.
<div class="mth">ΔT = T_component − T_reference

T_reference options:
  1. Ambient air temperature (easiest)
  2. Similar component under same load (best)
  3. Component when new/cold (for trending)

Rule: ΔT is only meaningful at similar load conditions.
  A 20°C rise at 50% load is very different from
  a 20°C rise at 100% load — same ΔT, different severity.
  Always document load at time of thermographic inspection.</div></div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<h3>Live ΔT Classifier</h3>
<div class="field"><label>Component temperature (°F)</label><input type="number" id="dt-comp" placeholder="e.g. 135" oninput="calcDT()"></div>
<div class="field"><label>Reference temperature (°F) — ambient or similar component</label><input type="number" id="dt-ref" placeholder="e.g. 75" oninput="calcDT()"></div>
<div id="dt-result" class="result"></div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>NETA / NFPA 70B Severity Levels</h3>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Priority</th><th>ΔT (°C)</th><th>ΔT (°F)</th><th>Action required</th></tr>
<tr class="hl"><td class="pass">Priority 4</td><td>1–3°C</td><td>2–5°F</td><td>Monitor — trend over time</td></tr>
