<div class="card">
<h3>Emissivity — Why Shiny Metal Fools IR</h3>
<div class="eli5"><strong>ELI5:</strong> An IR camera measures infrared radiation emitted by a surface. The emissivity of a material determines what fraction of thermal energy it emits as radiation vs. reflecting from the environment. Shiny metal has very low emissivity (~0.05) — it mostly reflects other objects' heat rather than emitting its own. A shiny bus bar may appear cool on an IR camera even when very hot, because it's reflecting the cool room temperature.
<div class="mth">Apparent temperature issue:
  Shiny copper bus at 100°C:
  IR camera reads ≈20°C (reflecting room!)
  
  Fix: Apply matte paint, tape, or Tempilaq to the surface
  to increase emissivity to ~0.95 before measuring.
  
  OR: Measure at a lug or wire insulation nearby — these
  have high emissivity and reflect actual temperature.</div></div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Material</th><th>Emissivity</th><th>IR accuracy</th></tr>
<tr><td>Polished copper/aluminum</td><td>0.02–0.05</td><td class="fail">Very poor — misleading</td></tr>
<tr><td>Oxidized copper</td><td>0.6–0.7</td><td class="warn">Moderate</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wire insulation (PVC)</td><td>0.90–0.95</td><td class="pass">Good</td></tr>
<tr><td>Painted surfaces</td><td>0.90–0.97</td><td class="pass">Good</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rubber, plastic</td><td>0.85–0.95</td><td class="pass">Good</td></tr>
<tr><td>Black oxide / anodized</td><td>0.80–0.90</td><td class="pass">Good</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
